animal.description:
*Name: Maddox
*Age: 2 years
*Current Weight: 37 lbs
*Health: up to date on required vaccinations, neutered, microchipped, Heartworm+

Maddox is a wonderful pup! He wants to get all the love - and he will give all his love right back! 

Maddox loves going for walks and exploring the world. He has fun running circles in the yard and enjoys a good play session. He is very patient with kids, and enjoys hanging out with them. In the evenings, he is part of the family hanging out on the sofa and watching TV. 

He is a super engaging pup with a great little personality - he makes us laugh often. His tail wags often, but when he’s super excited, his whole body wags. Maddox will be a bit nervous the first couple of weeks, but will soon settle in and be a wonderful, loving companion.

Maddox is heartworm positive and started his treatment in November. He will come with 6 months of Heartguard. 

To apply to adopt Maddox, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 
**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records. Remember, most of the time rescues are all just taking our best guess with breeds!

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Hi world! My name is Zoro! I'm 1.5 years old, 65 lbs, and a Boxer mix who recently arrived in Wisconsin from Oklahoma! I'm friendly, gentle, goofy, and I love to go for walks and play, but I also love to snuggle up on the couch for cuddling and napping.

I love to be outside, and I walk with a loose-leash most of the time! I'm usually quiet when I'm walking, and mostly like to concentrate on sniffing! When I see other dogs on walks, I sometimes get excited, but I don't usually need to say hello to them. After I go on my morning walk, I definitely need to take a tap to recuperate! I like relaxing and napping just as much as I like my outside time.

I love playing with toys, too! I play by myself a lot, but I like when my foster mom plays fetch with me, too. My foster mom says I'm a goofball when I play with toys and that's when my silly personality really comes out. 

I also just love meeting people! I'm a very friendly dog and I've gotten along with all of the humans I’ve met! I like being pet and being near people a lot. I’m also working on learning to be alone, too. Right now, it’s best that I stay in my kennel while people are gone. I go in there easily and I’m comfortable and cozy in there. 

I'm still adapting to living life inside of a home. There are a lot of new noises and people, and sometimes that scares me a bit. When I'm scared, I pace around my house and whine to show you that there's something making me uncomfortable. I need a future forever family who has patience to help me learn that the world isn't scary, and slowly introduce me to new things. I shouldn’t be in a home with a cat, but I get along with other dogs and many people!

If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website-?www.luckymuttsrescue.org?and submit an application. Our application process includes landlord approval and vet checks. Please make sure all of your information is current and accurate, including a valid email address and phone numbers. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and/or cancel your application. We strive to process all applications in a timely manner, but with the high volume of applications we are receiving, it is taking anywhere from 1-3 weeks.  You may be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions.  Once all of your information is reviewed and if your application is approved, you will be notified via email.  Submitting an application and receiving an approval does not guarantee you will be adopting the dog you applied for.  Once you move to the meet and greet process, you will be contacted by the foster family to further discuss the dog, and answer questions you may have, and if applicable, a meet and greet will be set up at our adoption center.   Meet and greets are only set up with approved applicants, and we require all members in the household to be present, as well as any current dogs in the home. 
Current Adoption Fees Are:$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
Bonded pairs vary
The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test, (if over 6  months) and a certified veterinary inspection. Please be aware, listed dog breeds are based on information provided and cannot be guaranteed.  Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen, we receive several applications for each dog. Our adopters are picked based on the needs of the dog, and the home we feel with best fit based on your responses to our application, vet information and landlord requirements.   Approved applicants not chosen for the dog you applied for, will be in active status for a period of six months.  We encourage you to watch Petfinder, Facebook and our website for upcoming dogs.  Should you see a dog that interests you,please send us a Facebook message or an email with your approval number.  Please be patient with us, as Lucky Mutts Rescue is run strictly by volunteers and many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thank you for considering Lucky Mutts Rescue for your next furry family member!

animal.description:
ADOPT ME ONLINE: https://ophrescue.org/dogs/10302

Biscayne is a 2-year-old, 33-pound cattle dog mix that is deep down a big teddy bear. He loves to cuddle up in bed and take up lots of space! Belly scratches are his favorite and he will let you know when he wants more. He would do best in an area with lots of space to run and easy access to an area to go to the bathroom. He is a bit shy of other dogs and vocal when he sees others he doesnt know. 

He knows to sit and even scratches at the door for you when he needs to go out, so listen carefully! Biscayne is also an energetic dog and could run on and on but will love to cuddle up with you on the couch. He is also dealing with a bit of separation anxiety when left alone or when his favorite person leaves but is just out of love. If you have any other questions let me know!
To adopt this dog, or any OPH dog, fill out the simple online application at https://ophrescue.org 
Operation Paws for Homes, Inc. (OPH) rescues dogs of all breeds and ages from high-kill shelters in NC, VA, MD, and SC, reducing the numbers being euthanized. With limited resources, the shelters are forced to put down 50-90% of the animals that come in the front door. OPH provides pet adoption services to families located in VA, DC, MD, PA and neighboring states. OPH is a 501(c)(3) organization and is 100% donor funded. OPH does not operate a shelter or have a physical location. We rely on foster families who open their homes to give love and attention to each dog before finding a forever home.

animal.description:
This beautiful 40 lbs mix is a delightful companion on my jogs in the hills, but a little slow for my daughter’s 8-9 minutes mile running pace. After a jog, he is super chill for the rest of the day. He will try to chase cats, squirrels and big birds, but is easily distracted when I use his harness and voice. He will growl at other dogs when they come too close, so likely will need a lot of training, or, better, be in a home with no other dogs or cats.

He sure acts very youthful and is wonderfully lively for his age of 10. Potty trained, quiet and sleeps well at night. He was a bit fearful of us at first, but after a few weeks of cuddles and love, he comes bounding up to us now when we get home. He has been friendly to all of our family and to kind passers by who want to pet him. We will miss him! He is a true love!!

A little bit about Tali, he came to Hopalong from a hoarding case, he lived most of his life in a crate. He had horrible skin, dental and other issues. He is all healthy now and happy! After living several years without much socialization we hope he finds the best home.

*Needs to be in a home with no dog or cat*

** WANT MORE INFO OR THINKING OF ADOPTING THIS PET? **

animal.description:
Sweet Gypsy!  She weighs just under 40 lbs and is approx 1.5 years old.  She was saved from a shelter where she was brought in with her litter of puppies.  We have done a DNA on her and she is basically part American Staffordshire Terrier, American Bull Dog with small percentage of Jack Russell Terrier. Gypsy was apparently never socialized with people and is very very cautious and timid.  She has been with one of our fosters since late October and has slowly been coming out of her shell.  This is what we have learned about Gypsy:  She most definitely needs a social, playful dog in the household.  A fenced in yard is a must.  She loves ......loves to play outside.  When she comes back in the house she, for the most part, likes to stay in her “safe spot” whether its a doggy bed or a crate.  She is housebroken if kept on a schedule.  A good routine is best for Gypsy.  Once she got to know her foster, she does follow her around the house and now gets very excited to see her when she comes home from work and has to be acknowledged and petted right away.  Gypsy at this time cannot be leashed walked.  We are going to insist that she be adopted locally within the Richmond/Chesterfield area.

We do have some videos of her playing with her canine buddy at her foster home.  Serious inquiries only.  Potential adopter needs to understand she will take lots of time and patience in her new home.  No children under 16 years old please. 

Gypsy is a wonderful, beautiful, very sweet girl but  we do not feel she will never be a lap dog but you never know.  We want a serious adopter that will spend lots of time letting her chase balls outside and playing with another dog.   Once she comes inside, she is very quiet and content. 
 
Approved application and adoption fee of $225.  She is updated on vaccinations, heartworm negative, on hw and flea preventative, spayed and microchipped.

You can contact Pam Danford @ 804-229-4043 for more information about Gypsy.

Roo is a pretty red heeler about 1 1/2 years old.  She was surrendered in Brigham City, after being passed around to several different people, and then given up.  She is medium sized, about 40 lbs. She is not house trained, but does well in a crate.  She is good with most other dogs.  She can be stubborn and snappy when you want her to do something she doesn't want to do, like go out to potty when it's cold.  She needs someone who has had heelers before and knows their quirks and personality, and won't let her get away with being the boss.  She has great inside manners.

Roo is looking for a forever family to call her own. Her adoption fee is $200, which includes spay surgery and vaccinations (parvo/distemper and rabies.) If you would like to meet this dog, please email us: scfourpaws@hotmail.com or leave a message @ 435-764-3534. Please be patient with us getting back to you as we are all volunteers with full-time jobs. Thanks for your interest in this wonderful dog!!

animal.description:
“'An absolute love . . . just wants to be with her family . . . enjoys long walks but doesn’t need constant activity . . . '  Those are some of the glowing descriptions provided by my foster family.  What more needs to be said!?

Well, there is more.  My fosters report that I am good on the leash, great with their teenagers and I seem to be house trained.  I am generally well behaved (Though I did steal bacon off the table one time – but really . . .  bacon within reach.  Can you blame me?).  I love pets and cuddles.  I know sit and paw, and I catch treats like a champ.  Who knows what else you can teach me!  I could also likely live with the right doggie sibling.

Prior to PAC, I was found as a stray in Florida, and no one came to claim me.   I sure act like I have known family home life.  Will you be the one to provide it for me forever?

‘Nuff said.  Please come check me out.  Some details:

I'm about 6 years old, around 58 pounds, microchipped, spayed and up to date on my vaccinations. 

So, if you are interested in more information about me and/or would like to set up a meeting with me, please send a completed adoption profile (found here - https://providenceac.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Adoption-Profile.pdf) to foster@providenceac.org today!

XOXO – Reba


P.S. Someone is so excited for me to find my fur-ever home, that they have sponsored my adoption fee! That means I can join your family today for FREE! Woohoo!!" 

___

Providence Animal Center relies on adoption fees and donations to save pets! Adoption fees vary per pet. To find out this pet’s adoption fee or for more information, please call the Adoption Center with this pet’s ID number.

Can’t adopt? Consider fostering or donating! Visit https://providenceac.org/support-us/ for more information on how you can support the lifesaving mission!

animal.description: Hi all! I'm Hazel, of the sometimes lopsided ears! I have big, wonderful, weird ears that want to stand up straight but just can't manage it all of the time. I'm a smaller terrier mix who is a tawny-golden-hazel color, with two white socks on my front feet. I'm a looker! But here's the thing -- I need a very experienced owner, one familiar with my breed. No first-time dog owners for me. And I just cannot live with cats, critters, other dogs, or children under 12 years old. That's a lot of restrictions, I know! But I'll be all the dog  you'll need. I'm curious, athletic, and eager to learn. I arrived here as a stray, and it's clear I haven't been given a chance to be a good girl. A skilled owner, plenty of exercise, and ongoing obedience classes could be great for me.

animal.description:
What is your name?

I’m Goulash, but they like to call me GOO!

How old are you?

I am right about a year old now (as of January, 2021).

What do you look like?

I’m about 45 pounds, have cropped ears, and I’m a blue-ish fawn color!

What do you like to eat?

Pretty much anything. I don’t really get a sensitive belly.

What kind of personality do you have?

I am pretty easy going! I love chewing on bones, playing inside, and being near my people! Cuddling is great, too.

Describe your perfect day

A nice walk in the am, followed by a nap on my bed and some treat training in the afternoon! Maybe a trip to the pet store?

What is your favorite toy?

BALLS! Durable rubber balls and water buffalo horns are the best!

Do you know any tricks?

Um… I can sit, look handsome, and stay for a few seconds for you to catch a picture!

What scares you?

I don’t like a lot of loud voices or physical roughhousing, but I’m not necessarily scared. I just tend to avoid those moments.

Do you like cats?

They are really interesting! My foster home has some and I have been learning all about leaving them alone and I’m doing really well! I just want to play, but mostly understand that they don’t want to play with me.

Do you have any doggie best friends?

No, I’m not allowed to have doggie best friends because I don’t like to share.

If you could be anywhere in the world, where would it be?

On. The. Couch.

How is your health?

I’m pretty good now! When I came to EC I had some colon issues and a UTI but I am long past them now! I have had surgery to repair these issues and I’m doing awesome! I was just neutered in January 2021, too.

How long have you lived in your foster home?

I’ve been with a member of Even Chance since around October 2020

Who do you live with in your foster home and who is your closest companion?

My foster mom for sure! The kitties are ok, though. ?

Where do you hang out when you are home alone?

I always hang out in my crate when there aren’t any people home.

Where do you sleep?

I always sleep in my crate at night, but while my family is home, I will lay on my bed or snuggle on the couch.

What do you love about your foster family?

I love that my foster family is so dedicated to meeting all my needs. I am grateful that Even Chance rescued me!

What was life like before you were rescued by Even Chance and brought into the welcoming arms of your foster parents?

I was surrendered to a shelter because my first home couldn’t meet my medical (colon) needs.

Even Chance does not operate on a first come, first serve basis. In most cases we have already decided the type of home and owner we want for our dogs. These opinions are based on the temperament tests we perform prior to accepting the dog into our program and the behaviors the dogs display as they spend time in our homes. Our agency reserves the right to deny acceptance of any dog to an owner who we feel the lifestyle does not match that of the dog. We are in no way judging you or your lifestyle; we simply want to put our dogs in the best living situation possible. We take very seriously the decision we make when it comes to placing one of our dogs in a forever home. If I sound like the perfect pit bull for you and your family and you are interested in giving me a forever home, do not hesitate! Please fill out an application here and my foster family will contact you to schedule an in-person meet and greet. We look forward to meeting any and all interested applicants.

animal.description:
Meet Bayou! He is a 9 month old yellow lab greyhound mix. He is super friendly and loves people and other dogs. He loves to play and run and run. Which is probably how he found himself lost and almost drown in a water filtration plant in rural Louisiana. Thank goodness he was found when the worker came in that morning or he wouldn't have made it much longer. He couldn't get out by himself. He was seen by the vet and he wasn't injured and the nasty water didn't hurt him. 

This boy will need a secured fenced in yard to be able to run and play in. He will need a family to help teach him some manners and that jumping isn't appropriate. He is learning very quickly and is definitely treat motivated. He is scheduled to be neutered in 2 weeks. He is up to date on shots, rabies, dewormer, on heartworm prevention, and microchipped. To adopt Bayou apply at CanineHavenRescue.org under available adoption tab. His adoption fee is $350

animal.description:
Otis is a wonderful happy pup born Feb. 2020 to a stray momma in Tyler, TX. They went to another rescue for a bit but ended up here when the other rescue had too many dogs to
care for.

Otis is energetic and loves to play, but when you're done playing, he will climb into your lap to cuddle. He's a total sweetheart. He thinks he's a lap dog - it's pretty cute. This little guy is has the most soulful eyes. He is a real heart stealer! Otis has done great with children and does really well with the other dogs in his playgroup. Otis is submissive with other dogs, but just wants to play and be near them. He would do well with a doggie companion in his forever home. We think Otis would do best in a home with a yard, as we do not think apartment life would suit him. He would love to have a big yard to run around and play fetch with you. Otis takes anxiety medication daily to make him feel less nervous and more comfortable. The medication is really no big deal. It's extremely inexpensive, readily available, and makes Otis feel happy and well-adjusted. He can still be a little nervous with new people and places(which is understandable, given his background), so he will need a patient adopter that will allow him adequate time to decompress and adjust to his surroundings.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi, I'm Drummer! My family thinks I'm about 2 years old in human years, but still have some puppy in me so who knows! I'm 48 pounds, black and tan and was neutered in December, which gave me lots of excuses for cuddles. I still have a little growing to do, but I'm still a puppy at heart! I'm still learning commands, but I'm a very quick learner and have basic manners down (even though I'm still learning how to play gentle). I'm house-broken, crate-trained, and very conscious of the rules of the house (no furniture for me unless you tell me!). I'm calm in the car since I know I'll be on my way for an adventure, sometimes I'll even fall asleep for the ride! Though I act tough at first, I like meeting new people and will bond quickly with my family! Everyone always tells my mom how handsome I am and how funny I am when I try to tell them thank you (guess no one speaks dog)! I love playing with other dogs (big and small) and have met a few kids and a cat, but I'm not 100% sure about them just yet. Once I get used to a space and people, I am a great companion and will follow you anywhere! Ideally, I want a backyard with a buddy to play with. My mom takes me on walks, but nothing compares to herding friends at the dog park or getting cuddles before a nap! If you think you can offer me my furever home, please contact your adoption coordinator. If you do not have an adoption coordinator, please complete an adoption application at https://freedomgermanshepherdrescue.org I am being fostered in Wilmington.

animal.description:
Queen Lilly! 

This Old lady found herself homeless in the shelter at 10 years of age. No family to take care of her, We gladly took her into the Dog Days family.

Once in foster care we realized she was not properly socialized with other dogs. She simply does not know how to interact appropriately with other dogs.

We have also learned she is fun, spunky, energetic, loves to snuggle or play with toys/chew bones.

We are looking for a place for this senior to lay her head and be spoiled for the rest of her years. A place where she can be queen of the castle as an only pet.

Lilly is about 40 lbs She walks well on leash. Lilly is crate trained and house trained.

Adoption fee $ 150 includes spay/neuter, up to date on vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative. Lily had a dental completed in November 2020. 

If you are interested in adopting fill out an application at https://www.petstablished.com/pets/public/906736 by clicking on the adopt button.

 

Dog Days in a small, foster based Rescue based out of Kennesaw, Ga.

We have some amazing babies waiting for their forever families to find them. All of our babies are spayed/neutered, current on vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative or have been treated for heartworm.

Due to Covid-19 we are not holding our normal Petco Adoption Days. Instead we are scheduling one on one meet and greets with approved applicants.

If you see a dog you are interested Please fill out an application. Once approved we will schedule a meet and greet with the dog/dogs you are interested in. Meet a greets are held outside (when the weather permits) by appointment only and with a limited number of people with everyone wearing masks.

We are unable to process out of state adoptions at this time

He will need a fenced yard to run and play. No apartments as the finder tried that and it wasn’t a good fit for him.

He is currently undergoing heartworm treatment. He can be adopted now as long as he completes his treatment with our veterinarian.

LOKI ~2 year old. Good with older considerate kids and large dogs. Not good with cats or small dogs. Needs a companion animal

GSRA adopts to residents of VA, NC, and SC only

Loki is a gorgeous large male who will need to continue to work through his insecurities. He walks well on leash, he is non reactive to stressful situations. He is shy to new people and will need a family that will give him time to be comfortable with them. He's a rough physical player and needs a confident companion that can tolerate his play style as well as help him build his confidence when out and about. Loki is house trained and crate trained and a good car rider. Loki has a high prey drive so would be best without cats and his play style is too much for small dogs. Loki needs a family experienced with an under socialized dog. He would be a great running partner. With continued work, love and patience Loki will blossom into a more carefree, happy boy. If your New Years resolution was to get more exercise then Loki is the guy to help you.

animal.description:
Meet J-Jackson aka JJ! What a character this boy is?! He just lights up a room with his personality! He is a Black Lab male, approx. 2-3 years old, 56 - 60 pounds, super sweet with a Pepe Le Pew like banner of a tail!

J-Jackson was in front of a sheet metal shop for at least 4 weeks while workers fed and watched over him and then contacted us. Luckily we were able to capture him and bring him to safety. Turned out J-Jackson was adopted not long before from Cullman County Animal Control. The family who adopted him doesn't have a fenced-in yard. He regularly visited neighbors who gave him all different names, food, etc. The family agreed to allow us to rehome this wonderful boy to a home that could give him what he needs to stay safe!

JJ is housebroken, crate trained although prefers to be in one's lap and arms. He is a big love bug, hasn't chewed anything other than bully sticks and femur bones! He is talkative and thinks he is having human conversations with you! haha. He loves to eat, have treats, and mostly enjoys hugs! If you are interested in adopting or meeting any of our animals available for adoption you will need to FILL OUT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION ON OUR WEBSITE FIRST. Due to the volume of interest in our animals and the convenience we now offer of applying online for adoption, we are no longer able to reply to messages sent through our Petfinder page. MESSAGES RECEIVED THROUGH PETFINDER WILL GO UNANSWERED.
Copy and paste this URL link to learn everything you need to know about the adoption process and to fill out the application.
https://www.grandstrandhumanesociety.com/adopt/

Say hello to Scrap and Trooper! (Scrap is the bigger one) They are both very friendly, seemingly house trained, middle-aged dogs that seem fine with other dogs and lived with a cat.
Scrap is very nervous about strangers approaching and reaching into his crate! But really all he wants is to be let out on his own and then he’s fine. We have been working with him on this for a week and now he seems to be fine with people reaching into his crate. On a leash he seems to love everyone he meets! We even took him to the doctor to get his ear meds and he was PERFECT about it!
Trooper is one of the friendliest dogs ever as well! So sweet and happy to meet everyone (even in his crate lol).
They absolutely love each other and we really want to keep them together! It took a week or so before we could even walk them separately, and we think they would be really sad if separated.
These are WONDERFUL, friendly, well-behaved goofy angels! They were surrendered to us after their human mama passed away and no one could take them in. They did nothing wrong and could use a good home to help them though their tough time.

animal.description:
Zorro (aka Zeus) is an awesome 1-1/2 year old male Pit Bull Terrier who was surrendered by his owner on January 4, 2021 because he could no longer take care of him.  Zorro was accompanied by his beautiful companion (Baby Girl) who had shared his home.

Zorro has a tan short smooth coat with subtle blue/black shading, a tiny spot of white on his chest, a long tail, and a handsome face with beautiful brown eyes, a blue nose, and short semi-erect ears.

His owner told us that Zorro is good with children and also with other dogs.  He has been kept indoors and is still working on his housetraining skills.  Zorro has occasional accidents if left alone too long.  He is frightened of vacuum cleaners and cowers to show his fear.

His  favorite activity is playing with tug-of-war rope toys.

Zorro's only known behavioral issues are chewing and chronic escaping from his fenced-in yard.  So he needs close supervision to help him be a 'good boy' :)

Zorro weighs 50 lbs.  He is very energetic and strong on the other end of a leash.  Zorro tends to grab his leash thinking it is a great impromptu tug-of-war toy.

Zorro will be neutered before being adopted by his new family.

UPDATE: Zorro was neutered on January 25, 2021 and was also given rabies vaccine.

animal.description:
MEET BLEU!!

PLEASE NOTE: This dog is courtesy posted for another individual or Rescue. Different policies and fees may apply.

For more information or to schedule an appointment to meet this pet, please complete a Dog Adoption Questionnaire online at lostourhome.org You can also contact Lost Our Home at 602-445-PETS (7387) or email us at adoptions@lostourhome.org.

Here's what the day foster says about this special boy! Please read all about me to see if I would be the right fit for you........

Bleu is an incredible boy! It was our first time to meet and within the first half hour together he was comfortable and happy. He hopped right in and out of the car, waiting to be invited to hop out at our destinations. He enjoyed the car rides, either putting his nose out the window or being the perfect co-pilot.

Bleu LOVED every moment of our four-mile trail hike. He's active, athletic, engaging and genuinely happy. You find yourself smiling along with him. He's inquisitive and enjoys exploring. He discovered the creek bed and had the time of his life splashing around and running back and forth. He was well behaved with Tweety and Trumpet as his trail companions. He would look back to check that they were still behind him.

As a deaf dog
, he's very well adjusted and trusting of his handler. He bonds quickly and loves completely. He is everything a two-year-old boy should be, full of life. He will benefit from a home and family dedicated to his continued success and he will thrive as he continues to learn more as he so smart and engaged with his humans.

At one point, an older woman approached Bleu and he graciously accepted her pets. She walked with us for a bit while we talked and Bleu walked politely with us. She complimented his manners as she parted ways with us. He reads his "audience" very well for his age.

Bleu is an absolute treasure!

Hi folks! I am a full of energy pup who sure loves adventure. I like having a doggy companion who wants to romp and play with me. My current obsession...TOYS! Boy am I real sucker for my toys. I can coexist great in a home with small and large dogs that are READY TO RUMMMBBBLLLE but also know how to just chill and hang out sometimes and don't mind SHARING their toys with me too ;) I am a strong, handsome guy who needs a lot of exercise and play time to keep me looking so healthy and my spirit so youthful! I'll always take a break from activity for some cuddles though. I can walk well on a leash! I'm always on the go so apartment life is not really going to be my style.

I will do best in an adult home with no cats, that is set up for a big boy like me to have my own space. Another fun fact about me, I am deaf! This makes me hypersensitive to anything that causes vibrations through the ground. These weird objects vibrating the ground can make me reactive, but don't worry, I'm probably more scared than you are! Just take caution with things like vacuums and lawnmowers when I'm around...I'll want to protect you from them sucking you in!

I am working with our Lost Our Home dog behaviorist to learn some manners and become the best boy possible. If you are willing to continue my training, I will be the perfect doggo for you. Please apply if you would like to meet me and my foster mom can tell you how amazing I truly am!

All dog adoptions include the following:

--Spay/neuter surgery

--All current vaccinations

--Microchip with free chip registration

--Free wellness exam through VCA Animal Hospitals

--Access to our Behavior Helpline for the lifetime of the pet

--Two free one hour professional training sessions good for one year after the date of adoption

animal.description: Slinky is always on the move! She is about 9 months old and is a Boxer. She is full of typical Boxer wiggles and loves everyone she meets. Slinky is house trained with access to the yard at her foster home. She prefers only being in her crate at meal time, but is working on being fully crate trained. Slinky is outgoing and not a watch dog. She can be choosy with her dog friends and is working on not getting excited around other dogs in her foster home so for now, she needs to be the only dog in her forever home. She thinks kitties are for chasing so will also need a forever home without cats. She loves to play with toys and with her foster family. Slinky is an active dog that would love an equally active family that can keep up with her bouncy Boxer personality and give her plenty of mental and physical exercise every day. A walk around the block isn't going to cut it for this girl. She's ready for multiple walks, hikes, playing in the yard, and puzzles, training exercises and working on her basic obedience commands. After her energy is spent, Slinky loves to cuddle up as close as she can to you. She is the ultimate snuggler. She is fostered with two children and is very gentle with them. She would love kids in her forever home to play with and love on her. If you are interested in meeting Slinky, your first step would be to submit an adoption application on our website. If you are already approved with an adoption coach or have adopted from us before, reach out to your coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported, solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. animal.description:
Precious is a 10-year-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, 4dx/heartworm tested, and spayed. This dog is also tested with other dogs, kennel-trained, and housebroken. Precious would do best in a home with children over the age of 12. We would love for you to meet this dog and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
Baby Girl is a beautiful 3-year old female Pit Bull Terrier who was surrendered by her owner on January 4, 2021 because he could no longer take care of her.  Baby Girl was accompanied by her handsome companion (Zorro aka Zeus) who had shared her home.

Baby Girl has a tan short smooth coat with a large white bib on her chest, white socks on her paws, a long tail, and a gorgeous face with amber-colored eyes, white markings on her muzzle/forehead, a liver-colored nose, and short floppy ears.  

Her owner told us that Baby Girl is good with children and also with other dogs.   She has been kept indoors and is still working on her housetraining skills.  Baby Girl has occasional accidents if left alone too long. 

Baby Girl knows some basic commands (sit, speak, and shake).  She is frightened of loud noises and vacuum cleaners.    Baby Girl is protective of her toys and food.

Her favorite toys/activities are playing with squeaky toys, running, fetching, and tug of war. 

Baby Girl is being listed as a 'Special Needs Dogs' since she has shown signs of possible seizures.

Baby Girl weighs 57 lbs and is quite strong on a leash.  She has already been spayed.

animal.description:
Bella - Chi Mix - Female - 10 lbs - 13 yrs (approx.)
Diablo - Rat Terrier Mix - Male- 19 lbs - 12 yrs (approx.)

Do you want to say goodbye to 2020 and hello to 2021 with a double dose of love? This bonded couple might just be what your heart needs!

Here’s what you should know:
Diablo and Bella came to Save Me Dog Rescue after their elderly owner passed away. They are like two peas in a pod; everything they do, they do it together. They can often be found laying with their heads on each other for comfort. They would love to have a yard where they could run and play - they are excited and tend to pull on a leash. Their foster parents believe this would also help with their house training as they are not perfect, but they are working on it. Included with Diablo are some fashionable belly bands as he tends to mark in the house. They are crate trained and will only bark for the first few minutes when you leave and then quickly stop (their foster parents spy on them with a pet camera). They do well in the car and do not mind bath time. However, mealtime is their favourite time. They are currently on a raw diet and they absolutely love it. They have recently been getting into little arguments with one of the resident dogs; therefore, they would prefer a home with no other pets and no young children.

Saying Bella and Diablo are the perfect mix of silly and cuddly would be an understatement.  The question is…. Can you handle that much cuteness and love?

For more information on Bella & Diablo, please contact Marilyne at ellis.marilyne@gmail.com

OR visit our website: www.savemedogrescue.ca

** Adoptions within the province of Ontario only

animal.description:
Just as beautiful as her name would suggest, lovely Venus is a 5 year old, 52 pound Shepherd mix, whose soulful eyes will melt your heart. Gentle and affectionate, she loves to be stroked and have her belly rubbed. Venus is fully house trained, walks well on a leash, and has respectful indoor manners. She enjoys her walks and exploring the backyard but is very content to snuggle on the couch with you for hours.

Venus was found as a stray wandering outside with her daughter. Now safe with a foster family, she is loving her life off the streets. Initially timid and cautious, Venus has warmed up quickly and is now an incredibly sweet and loving part of the household who seeks affection frequently. She can still be tentative and unsure around new people and other dogs, but the patient support of a loving family will help her gain the confidence she needs while she adjusts to her new environment. Venus would probably do well in a home with kids over 10 years old. This girl truly is a goddess, and will make a wonderful addition to any home.


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.

animal.description:
We show our pets by appointment only upon receipt of our online application which can be found at kcpaws.petfinder.com  If you are reading this, we are still accepting applications for Cindy Lou.  The adoption fee for Cindy will be $175. 

Meet Cindy Lou! 

Cindy was living as a junk yard dog with a homeless man who was caring for her and multiple other dogs. When he was able to find housing, Cindy came to us to find a permanent home. Cindy LOVES other dogs and really enjoys playing in our playgroups. Meeting new people is still scary for Cindy, she needs time to warm up and build trust. She would do best in a calm home with patient owners who understand that she is scared, and will need some extra time to feel fully confident in a new environment. We believe having another dog in the home will be very important for Cindy to be successful in her new home. Cindy is friendly with big and small dogs. We aren't sure how she does with cats, but we are always willing to introduce her to any pets in the home. Because Cindy is so skittish, she needs a home with no young children. 

Cindy weighs about 65 lbs and is between 1 and 3 years of age.

If you are interested in adopting Cindy, please fill out our online application.

We are Peanut and Sugar, the dynamic duo!! We are sisters and are looking for a home together.

I am Sugar, a 9 year old, yellow female lab weighing in at a dainty 60 lbs. I am a shy girl when I meet new people but when I get to know them, I am the friendliest girl around. I love to play fetch and if there is no one around to throw the ball at me, I am happy playing by myself. I enjoy walks through the neighborhood and I am crate trained but I prefer to sleep on my doggie bed, I am also house trained. I know my name and how to sit. I love getting attention and getting my hair brushed. I enjoy car rides and snuggling.



Hi there! I am Peanut, a chocolate, 9 year old female lab weighing in at 60 lbs. Just like my sister, I am shy at the beginning and then warm up. I know my name and how to sit nicely and I bet I could learn more commands. I love walks around the neighborhood and hanging out with my sister. I really like treats but my favorite things are toys!!I love having them around me! I am crate trained but enjoy sleeping on my doggie bed. I love snuggles and getting affection from my humans.

We are looking for a home, hopefully with carpet or rugs, where we can hang out together and spend our golden years receiving snuggles.

animal.description:
This handsome fella is Scotty, a 4 year old Lab Retriever mix that would make the pawfect addition to your home! Sadly, Scotty was surrendered because he was having some behavioral issues in his previous home, that his owners were not able to help him with. They did say that the other dogs in the home would start fighting and he would join in after the fact, but he would never start fights himself. Scotty is a very sweet and friendly boy! All he wants is love and cuddles from his favorite people! Scotty is just the biggest love bug, the second he see's you his butt is already wiggling and his tail is wagging! Scotty doesn't know just how big he is and he does still think he is a little lap dog, so be prepared for him to climb into your lap every chance he gets! Scotty loves laying out in the sun and going for a nice little walk. He is a bit overweight and will need help from his new parents to shed a few pounds! His previous parents did say that he is great with kids, he just doesn't understand how big he is so he might do better in a home with older kids. They also said that he is good with other dogs, it's just when the other dog in the home would start a fight he would join in. He has never been around cats, though. Scotty has done incredible with the potty routine here, but may need a second to adjust to the routine in his new home. He is current on his vaccines, heartworm negative, microchipped and neutered so he's ready to make himself at home with you today! Come meet this sweet boy at the Waggin' Tails Adoption Center in Benbrook, open every day from 12-6 pm, by appointment!

*Please give us a call at 817-249-3647 to schedule an appointment!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please Click Here to Fill Out an Online Adoption Application!
****PLEASE DO NOT APPLY IF YOU HAVE SMALLER ANIMALS, OR MALE ANIMALS. WE WILL NOT ACCEPT YOUR APPLICATION FOR BOWIE IF WE CAN TELL YOU HAVE NOT READ HIS PROFILE. HE IS A VERY SPECIFIC DOG. WE WANT TO SEE HIM SUCCEED AND NOT FAIL, PLEASE UNDERSTAND!!!***

*****BOWIE IS CURRENTLY WORKING WITH A TRAINER 3X/WEEK AND IS DOING MUCH BETTER! WE WOULD LOVE IF HIS NEW OWNER WOULD LIKE TO KEEP HIS TRAINER AND WORK WITH HIM IN HOPES TO SUCCEED AS A WONDERFUL COMPANION DOG!*****

Bo is an Australian Shepherd/Great Pyrenees Mix. At 16 mo old, Bo is learning what its like to not have to live his life on a chain. He was never allowed in the house, and was surrendered to rescue because of his barking. Bo is a very smart boy and is eager to interact with people. He does ok with dogs, providing proper introductions are made, but has shown many signs that he would need to be an only dog (unless you have a very strong-willed LARGE dog like a Husky/Malamute/German Shepherd or Pyrenees.) . He's just a big goofy puppy that hasn't been taught proper manners or behaviors. Bo has a ton of potential to be an amazing boy!
ONCE AGAIN:(due to high volume of applications with smaller dogs): He would NOT DO WELL with smaller dogs, submissive dogs, or cats/critters of any kind.
HE WILL CHASE THEM WITH INTENT TO CATRCH THEM!!!
David Bowie was in a long-term foster home and has learned Basic Obedience, Crate training, Leash Manners(for the most part), as well as Potty Training and generally learning how to be in a home!!!

Bo LOVES people, and is a very affectionate dog!
Bo MUST go into a home with a 6 foot fenced in yard, NO EXCEPTIONS!!!
Bo MUST be an only dog unless you understand that he WILL have issues at first in the new home, and that it is not fair for him to dominate your older dog.
We will ONLY allow him to be in a home by himself, or with a STRONG female dog that is larger than 50lbs and younger than 5 years old.
He is VERY strong, and will need a strong owner and new family.
He would make a great property protection dog/farm dog as long as there are no loose animals, and will alert you if anyone is coming up your property.

He barks at cars/trucks on his walks so we think a home in the country would be PERFECT! 2/2/21 3:04 PM

animal.description:
Ghia is a two year old chihuahua mix. 7.4 lbs. She loves to be held and would make an excellent cuddle buddy. She does well with other dogs, particularly small dogs. Loves to sleep with you. She came from a home with senior woman, and that is the kind of home she is used to. Her owner passed away, and she is still adjusting to her new situation. But she's fit in well with our other dogs here.

Please find our applications and valuable information under "Adopt a dog"* on our website: www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.

Bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B. A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!

B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
Meet Romeo!!  Romeo was in a crowded shelter in Chicago and his fate was unknown.  He was surrendered with Juliet and Bella due to living in an apt.  Romeo was so scared and shutdown, his face shows his worry in his first picture.  
 
A ranch team member saw this face and was not going to let him continue to be so alone.  So... she went and got him and now look at him!!!  

He loves his foster sister, has a great appetite and loves to play ball.  His coat looks great and his worry seems to be gone.  Romeo takes a little time to warm up to people but if you go slow and let him come to you in his time, he tail will wag and you may get a kiss or two.  

Romeo would love to be with another dog and one who likes to play. He does great in the car too.  
If you think Romy is a good fit for your lifestyle and you have an arm that can throw... he may be your guy. Romeo would love a fence or someone who likes to go on daily runs/walks and can be committed to this daily.  Backpacking and Hiking would be fun too, he asked me to mention this.   

We have not tested him with children at this time.  Romeo is fully vetted and ready to go. 
  
If you are interested, please apply on our website
www.fourleggedranch.com
adoption fee is 250.00

Valerie- Female/Spayed Lab Retriever/Shar-pei Mix  Color: Black 10 months old 58.8 lbs.
ID# D-39977

Valerie was strolling by the shelter one day, came to visit and decided she wanted to stay. Now she's ready to find a family to love & spoil her. Valerie is a wonderful, sweet, girl who gets along well with other dogs, at 1st meeting, she is a little apprehensive when being introduced to other dogs, as if she's had a rough encounter with one in the past, but when she realizes they mean her no harm, she's good to go and has a loving personality. She will make a fantastic family dog. She will need a secured fence for exercise and play time, and the rest of the time, she needs to be indoors. She is mostly housebroken, and is working on those skills. Valerie would do best with an active family or a play buddy.

Valerie is current on basic vaccinations including Bordetella, been dewormed and is microchipped. She has tested Negative for Heartworms. 

Valerie has now been spayed as of 1/5/21 and received her required Rabies vaccination. 

For more information, please contact the City of Corsicana Animal Shelter at (903) 654-4928. The shelter is open Mon, Tues, Thurs and Fri from 12:00pm - 6:00pm and on Sat from 12:00pm - 4:00pm.

animal.description:
Snapshot of Comet!

Size? Medium but still growing!
Age? 4 months
Activity Level? I play hard and snuggle hard!
Noise Level? I like to bark occasionally when I play and when I see exciting things on walks!
Good with Dogs? I would love a playmate!
Good with Cats?

I like cats more than they like me! (Dog-savvy cats may be okay)

Good with Kids?
Older kids only please!

Good with Strangers?

I love everyone!

Potty Trained?
Working on it!

Crate Trained?
I bark some, but quick down quickly!

Interested? Learn more about Comet below!

About Comet:

My name is Comet! I'm a 4-month-old spayed female husky mix from South Dakota. I'm small right now but I am still growing! I came to Minnesota with my three siblings and have been living with my foster mom and her cat. I can't figure out why the cat doesn't want to play with me-I'm SO friendly! Other dogs tend to like me so I would love playdates! I get excited when I see them, but I'm gentle when meeting them, until they let me know it's OK to play. I haven't had any experience with kids, but I'm still working on not jumping up to say hi, so I'd probably do best with older kids only.

I am a curious, confident, spunky puppy who loves everyone I meet. Toys are the best, especially ones that squeak and ones I can chew on. Man oh man do I love to chew!! Sometimes I chew on things that aren't my toys, but I'm getting better at learning with what's OK and what's off-limits. I'm definitely smart, but I can also be stubborn, so I'm looking for a family that will be consistent and patient as I keep learning. After a long day of playing and exploring, I love to curl up on the couch with my foster mom.

I like my crate too, as long as you give me a treat when I go in. And I'm doing really well with potty training, as long as I have a consistent schedule. If I'm in the crate, I'll whine to let you know I have to go outside, but if I'm playing, I don't always remember to tell you before it's too late. Speaking of outside, I love the snow! I like to stick my face in it and eat it up. I'm pretty good at walking on a leash, too! I'm working on staying calm when I see other people or dogs on my walks. Eating things off the ground is also SO temptingI'm still working on "leave it." But I know "sit," "paw (shake)" and I'm working on following "come" and "stay" consistently.

I would do best in a home with someone who is patient and has time to spend being active with me and helping me learn what I need to know. I think I'd like living with another dog, as long as they have enough energy to play with me!

Adoption Fee: $550

Training Requirement: Obedience Training 1

*Foster to Adopt: I am looking for a forever home now, but I still need all my puppy shots! So I'm looking for a family that will be able to commit to bringing me to all of my appointments with TCPR until I'm ready to be fully adopted by you!

MEET ME/ADOPT ME: If you'd like to arrange a meeting or begin the adoption process, please fill out an adoption application by visiting www.twincitiespetrescue.org/adopt/adopt-a-dog/ . A volunteer from Twin Cities Pet Rescue will contact you once your application is reviewed.

FOSTER HOMES NEEDED!!! Twin Cities Pet Rescue is a volunteer-run, foster home-based organization. We can only rescue as many animals as available foster homes. Please consider saving the life of an animal in need and become a volunteer foster home today. To become a foster, fill out a dog or cat foster application on the Twin Cities Pet Rescue website: www.twincitiespetrescue.org . There is little to no cost to foster an animal. Twin Cities Pet Rescue provides its foster families with food, supplies, and veterinary care for its animals. All you need to do is supply the love!

PLEASE NOTE: Twin Cities Pet Rescue does not adopt to homes further than 60 miles from the Minneapolis/St. Paul Metro Area.

animal.description:
GUESS WHO IS FINALLY READY FOR ADOPTION!!!! THIS GUY!!

Meet Little Peep! Or as I like to call him "Meep Meep." Our little broken deaf chihuahua.

Peep is one of the saddest rescue cases I have worked with in my career. I got him on Easter Sunday when a friend called us with nowhere else to go. They had found a chihuahua running in the middle of the Parkway down in the oranges. He had what was originally thought to be a wound on his ear and was in a lot of pain. Because it was Easter no one would help and take him. So I said bring him to me and we rushed him to the hospital.

I often explain my first meeting of Peep like that old cartoon. The one where the big wooden crate is delivered and inside is a tiger roaring and snarling like crazy. When they handed me the crate that is what was inside. Literally a 9 lb monster lol. What did I get myself into?

When I looked at his ears I knew this was no wound. This was severe and chronic ear infections that had never been treated. He had quarter sized cysts blocking both ears and puss dripping down his face. To this day I have had 4 different vets tell me that Peeps ears are the worst they have ever seen.

I brought him home and started the long road to recovery with him. For the first week I could not even touch him. I spent a lot of time bribing him with cheese and chicken and his favorite, hot dogs. It was clear people had been cruel to him, it was clear he was abused, it was clear he had been through hell. With time he finally started to trust me. I do still have some battle wounds from that time, but in time He finally started to come to me. He quickly became my shadow.

2 weeks after I got him we did surgery on both ears. One was just a removal of the scar tissue, the other was a full TIKA to remove his ear canal and close his ear. The ear infections were so bad that we are just now 4 months later getting them under control.

This wasn't the end though of peeps medical issues. Shortly after the surgery Peep started to show neurological symptoms so we went to another doctor and did MRIs. It turns out he has bulging disk disorder of his upper back and neck. This is an issue that will affect him on and off throughout his life and he is on rymadel once a day for it. We have been weaning him off slowly but on bad weather days or if he tweeks it, it is still a necessity.

We also found out shortly after, that he has permanent nerve damage on the right side of his face. Due to the surgery and the damage from the neglect of his ears he has paralysis on that side. Due to this damage he cannot close his right eye and refuses to let me put drops in it. In time he will probably need that eye removed but not yet. Due to this there will be a medical stipulation that when the time comes he will have to be brought back to us for the removal. We will cover the cost and he can even stay with me for the recovery if needed.

For the past 4 months we have been battling his ear infections which are almost fully gone. He has been changed over to a limited ingredient food because we are pretty sure its an allergy, and although his ears are better he has a number of scars. One on his right eye is due to the puss over years collecting and ripping off. The hair in that spot will never grow back. People have failed him in so many ways.

I have to say His little deformed ears are actually my favorite part about him. His ears will probably continue to be an issue and he will probably need continual treatment throughout the rest of his life.

He is approx 6 to 8 years old. He has come so far in the past 4 months. He still gets snippy if I push his buttons or push his boundaries and takes a good long time to warm up to strangers, But otherwise he has become the sweetest most loving boy. He loves to snuggle, gives kisses, and get belly rubs. He likes to play and sleeps on my pillow or under the blankets with me every night. He is potty trained and has never had an accident in the house. He knows 4 hand signal commands and is learning more, and has a vibration collar we are training him on so he knows when we call him to come. He also loves my dogs and is a part of my pack. I'll be honest letting him go will be hard as I have considered keeping him often, however as the owner of Southern Paws, other dogs need me. My job is to rehab, and love, and care, but to also know when to let go.

This is his story. So now this is what we need.

An AMAZING PERSON lol willing to take him on with all his issues. There are people out there who love little broken dogs and that is what I'm looking for!

He can not be in a home with children! He needs an adult only home!

He can be with dogs and kitties though as long as they won't be overly in his face. I need a family with REAL EXPERIENCE who understands dogs and social queues and how to navigate them. I will be 100% honest. He will absolutely bite you if you do not read his signals. I have had him for 4 months and know how to navigate him. Learning this was not an easy task, and it will take time for his new owners to gain his trust and let him be messed with the way I mess with him.

You also must be willing to keep me updated on his progress and send me pics occasionally. I have grown super attached to my little land shark.

Please share!! I know that his person is out there somewhere!

If you are interested in little Peep. Please email us at southernpawsrescue@gmail.com for an application!

animal.description: Are you a person that enjoys seeing the world in black and white (no messy grey areas)? Do you like black and white things? Cows, newspapers, classic movies, a solid game of dominos? If you're that person, we've got the perfect dog for you. Meet Domino. Domino is a sweet boy who was initially found as a stray and after a little convincing, was more than happy to hitch a ride to PACC with our friendly animal protection officer (it was the promise of our gourmet Thanksgiving meal that sold him.) He was adopted out shortly after, but it wasn't a perfect fit, so he's back with us for the holidays. While Domino is excited to indulge in a second special holiday meal at PACC (Christmas Day is also no joke around here when it comes to food) he'd really love to get out of the shlter and into a home. Since arriving at PACC, Domino has shared his kennel with dogs he's just met and did well. In play group, he was appropriate with his greetings and happy to engage in a little bit of play with other pups. He's not very experienced walking on a leash, and would love his new owner to show him what that's all about. Domino is a nice boy who would love to get out of a shelter and back into a home of his very own. If you think you're the right person, make an appointment to meet him today.

animal.description:
Meet Jersey (formerly Fred)!!! Many of you saw Jersey in my live feed from a few months ago. Poor little guy was a mess. He had no fur!!! Well now isn't he beautiful?!? This dapper gentleman is a 1 year old basset hound pittie mix who is a low rider. He is approx 28lbs of energy and love. He is sweet and submissive and loves his 4 legged foster brother. He loves to run and play and is full of puppy energy. He is potty trained and crate trained and working on his manners. He definitely needs an active family. Due to his energy level older kids would be better for him as he could jump up and knock down a toddler. He hasn't been cat tested but we can arrange that if someone interested has feline friends!  He is the sweetest boy!
Jersey does have allergies and is allergic to everything lol. He needs to be on special prescription food that will run about 100 dollars a bag but it's working so to us that's all that matters. He also needs citopoint injections or apaquil a few times a year during season changes and high allergy times. I know this sounds like alot but this sweet guy is totally worth it. He is the best dog and has such a sweet playful temperament. He will make a wonderful addition to just about any family.
If interested in adopting Jersey please email us at southernpawsrescue@gmail.com for an application!

My name is Rook, but my foster Mom calls me Rookie Cookie. I am a male terrier mix, about 18 lbs. I am neutered and UTD on shots. The vet thinks I am 10-12 years old so I say I am 11.

I was found as a stray so I am now learning about living in a house. I am very friendly and love all people. I have lots of energy but I like to cuddle, too. I am working on house training but don’t get it yet. So I wear a belly band in the house. I have some skin issues but it has been treated and now I use special shampoos. I have a slight heart murmur, but take my meds and feel fine! I’m being fostered by Kathi in Cincinnati.

animal.description:
Basil is a quirky puppy with some manageable special needs who is looking for a home. Basil likely has Cerebellar Hypoplasia, a condition where the cerebellum is underdeveloped which leads to balance issues. He is also blind (he is too young to tell if hes entirely blind or if he can see a little bit). When Basil walks, he takes big, exaggerated steps and slams his paws down. Sometimes they even make a suction/squeaky sound! He wobbles from side to side and sometimes falls down if he is extra excited or playing. One of his favorite pastimes is spinning in circles (only clockwise - dont ask him to switch it up). Cerebellar Hypoplasia (CH) is diagnosed by a vet who looks at the symptoms. CH does not hurt and there is no treatment. Circles and wobbles are all Basil has known and he is okay with it. However, between the CH and blindness there are some things were looking for in his future home. If youve read the information below and think youd be a good fit, please email braveanimalrescue@gmail.com or fill out an application on our website at www.brave-animal-rescue.org.

Make sure you watch this video of Basil in action! https://youtu.be/_eR6hCCQ1Cc

Basils perfect home
-Carpeted floors or several rugs to help with stability and traction
-Minimal stairs 
-Easy access to yard (little to minimal stairs - FENCED)
-An easy-going dog sibling. Basil LOVES the dogs in his foster home and would benefit greatly from a companion. He is clumsy and will walk over sleeping animals so a calm and patient dog would be ideal. 
-No children under 13. Being blind and wobbly means Basil needs people who can be gentle and watch his body language. 
-Financially stable. Right now, Basil does not need any special treatment or medication. His conditions (blindness, CH) cannot be cured and it just gives him character! In case other issues present in Basils life, we want him to have a family who will be committed to taking care of whatever he needs. 
-Patience with potty training. Basil IS showing improvement with potty training. He knows where the back door is and he heads that way if he needs to go potty. He just usually goes before he gets there or before his foster mom sees his signal. He wears bellyband diapers when left alone for long periods of time. 

Other things to note
-Basil is estimated to be between 5-6 months old. He is likely a German shepherd mix and is currently 20 lbs. 
-Basil likes very short walks! He is learning to walk on a leash but dont expect perfection. There will be lots of spinning in circles. 
-He has not been kenneled. His foster mom tried to kennel him but he did not like being confined (no space to spin!!!). He is gated in the kitchen at night and when she leaves the house and he is content. 
-Basil does well with cats. He is too slow and uncoordinated to chase or bother them! 
-He is still learning to use the stairs. Right now, they pose a big challenge. He is carried outside when he needs to go potty but that might not be possible as he gets bigger. Its hard to say if he will ever independently master the stairs but he is having practice with his foster mom holding his harness. 
-Basil LOVES comfy dog beds. He has his foster home mapped out and will effortlessly travel from bed to bed. 

We believe Basil is a purebred German Shepherd who was born around 7/22/2020. This puppy is fostered in a private home in Lincoln. The adoption fee is $400.00 which covers vaccines, a microchip, and a spay/neuter(when old enough). The adoption fee helps cover the cost of these vetting procedures. Unless the bio is marked adoption pending, s/he is still available for adoption. If youre interested in adopting this puppy, please submit an inquiry or email BraveAnimalRescue@gmail.com to ask about our adoption process (please check your spam or junk email if you do not hear back from us within a few business days). We are 100% volunteer staffed and will respond to your email as soon as possible. After you have submitted an application and been approved, we will set up a meet and greet between you and the puppy. Preference is given to applicants with a verifiable vetting history, fenced yard, and homeownership. Please be sure to follow us on Facebook and Instagram to learn more about Brave Animal Rescue and our mission.

animal.description:
DOB: 09/18/2020

We are currently accepting applications to adopt Daisy. If you are interested in meeting and adopting her, please submit an adoption application by visiting our website (www.HarborOfHopeDogRescue.org). Due to COVID19 safety measures, meetings are currently only being scheduled with approved adopters.

Daisy enjoys lots of play time and snuggle time! She is doing very well with potty training and kennel training. She sleeps all night, eats and has downtime in the kennel. Daisy can be very vocal at times and for this reason she will NOT be a good fit for housing with any shared walls with neighbors. 

Like the flower she is very bright. She is learning to sit and be patient for treats. If there are other dogs in the home, Daisy would do best with a bigger dog who likes to play. Daisy is full of puppy energy. This pup will play hard and sleep hard. Snuggling on the couch at the end of the day hearing her little snores is the best! Daisy will be a lap dog for life!

All of our dogs are fully vetted before adoption, including vaccinations, spay/neuter, and a microchip.

The adoption process consists of an online application, a vet reference, two personal references, and a home visit. If approved to adopt, there is an adoption contract and an adoption amount. The adoption amount for Daisy is $375 and goes toward the vetting and care of all the dogs in our rescue.

All adoptions will take place in the Omaha NE area and must be done in person. We are willing to adopt to out-of-state applicants, contingent on our ability to complete a home visit, but you must be willing to come to the Omaha area to complete the adoption. We do not ship, transport or deliver our dogs.

If you would like to learn more about Harbor of Hope Dog Rescue, please visit our website (www.HarborOfHopeDogRescue.org) or our Facebook page. Thank you for your support!

animal.description: Holly is a 1-2 yr Pit bull mix. She is loose, wiggly and happy! She will sit next to her person without being called. Holly likes to give kisses! She is high energy so this gal would need plenty of playtime and exercise! Holly pulls on a leash but with some basic obedience training, this could easily be resolved. Holly is food motivated. She knows the sit command. Holly is not a fan of cats in a shelter environment. Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Our cat test should be used as a general purpose screening only to rule out overt aggression; we always recommend caution when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; JHS believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. Always remember that the majority of dogs at our shelter have been exposed to or may have kennel cough. Kennel cough is contagious to other dogs, please talk to your vet if you have any questions about kennel cough prior to adoption. Please ask your adoption counselor at time of adoption if you have any unanswered questions regarding illnesses and treatments of the path that you are adopting. For more information about this dog or any others at our Shelter, please visit www.joplinhumane.org. We are the Joplin Humane Society in Joplin, Missouri. 417-623-3642 I AM SPONSORED!
