animal.description:
Meet Baxter!

Baxter enjoys being an independent little fella. Although he is small does not mean he likes to be a lap dog all the time. He likes to be the one who initiates interactions first. Once, he feels comfortable around you he will then slowly start to warm up to you. He is most confident when he is with his friend Chica. They bring the best out of each other. 

He is working on coming out of his shell and not being so shy. He has a protective side and is learning how to put his guard down. Once, he knows he can trust you he will gladly sit by your side and enjoy some belly rubs. 

Baxter's ideal home is a quite place where he can relax and enjoy his days peacefully. He would benefit from a home with another fur sibling as along as they were as mellow as he is. Since, he likes to do his own thing and prefers not to be picked up all the time little kids are probably not the best fit. Baxter is just a chill dude looking for someone who is ready to settle down and live life one day at a time!

This good looking lady is Laney, a 3-4 year old Labrador retriever mix.  She has a striking smooth brindle coat and weighs 44 pounds and this is full grown.  Laney was pulled from our local animal shelter where she had been picked up by Animal Control and down there for over 2 months so we knew she needed to come on out.  

She is a super sweet, loving dog! Laney is very social otherwise, enjoys playing and being loved on, and going for walks on the leash.  She has a nice energy level so she may do ok in an apartment if she gets daily exercising.  

Laney will require a fenced in yard if left outside any off leash.  Laney should be fine around children.  We do allow a trial with an approved application.  We have started on her crate training.  Laney is up to date with her vet care, spayed, heartworm negative and microchipped.  She is on heartworm and flea/tick prevention.  

Such a beautiful dog, Laney is very ready to find her forever home in this new year!

Meet Rivers, 4 year old male Labrador retriever/pit bull terrier mix.  He has a smooth black and white coat and is a good size dog weighing 48 pounds.  Rivers was pulled from our local animal shelter where he had been picked up by Animal Control as a stray and no one came to claim him.  

This fine fellow is the life of the party!  He is fun, energetic, playful and loves all the attention he can get!  Rivers loves to run and play so he will need an active owner.  He is probably too energetic for an apartment and he will require a fenced in yard so he can get his energy out.  But he is not to be an outside only dog, he loves to be with his pack way too much for that.  

He got along well with the dogs he has been tested with and should be fine with children 12 and over.  He is jumpy so could easily accidently knock over a young child.  We have started on his crate training.  Rivers is up to date on his vet care, will be neutered prior to adoption, heartworm negative and is microchipped. Such a happy, fun dog – what a great way to start the new year off right by adding joy to your life with Rivers!

animal.description:
Bucky - around 18 months. Needs a home with a yard and another social dog. Kids over 12 only.

Sweet Bucky is a medium sized boy with incredible greenish eyes. He weighs just 40 lbs and we expect him to gain a few but will remain medium in size. So handsome.

He's had a rough start and we're so happy to be here for him! Rescued from Georgia, he's ready become a Pacific Northwest boy with a loving family so he can leave it all behind. He deserves it. It will take special people to give him confidence and in time, he will be soo happy.

Bucky is a very sweet and gentle boy. He is very timid around people but is slowly blossoming. He thrives in the company of other dogs and must be in a home with another social dogs to help him build confidence. He is a little skittish still at times and for this reason we would like to see him with older kids only (12 and up). He will do best in a more quiet residential area, rather than on busy city streets.

Bucky is beautiful and so charming!

He is now updated on all shots, neutered and chipped. His adoption fee is $395.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
Please read the entire description before contacting us.
We do not adopt out of state
We do not adopt to families with children under the age of 10 years old
You must live within 1.5 hours of Vallejo, CA
If the animal is posted they are available.
We cannot guarantee any of our available dogs are "hypoallergenic" 
All the information we have about them is in their description.
If you are interested in adopting a dog from us please review our process and complete our application at www.gunterslegacy.org/adopt.  

She’s a very energetic little dog and can easily walk three or 4 miles at a fast clip and still be ready for more. I also take her on 1 to 2 “smelling walks“ daily, Where she’s allowed to just sniff and go slowly. In my opinion, she’s super smart and needs a lot of exercise and adventure.

She definitely shows separation anxiety when I leave, but now will eventually settle down and nap or seek comfort from the guys.

However, just like my last terrier, she will run away any chance she gets and is always on the lookout for an escape opportunity. Her new family should be aware of this fact and know she cannot be left unattended in a yard or off-leash and must always wear a harness, collar, and tags.

In general, she really enjoys food and treats, especially hard chewies. For training, she is just as happy to get affection, so we train her with praise and cuddles.

Today I accidentally waved a hairbrush near her and she retreated in terror, shaking. It took a while to calm her. Pretty clear someone used to hit her. 

She mostly goes potty outside, (praise, praise, praise) but we still put down a pad at night just in case.

She has just now begun to exhibit playful behavior with our family. So far, she hasn’t shown any interest in other dogs (4 lbs to 85). I still think if she were in a household with small dogs who could model playful behavior, she would pick it up quickly.

She’s vomited every time she’s ridden in the car, so probably not a “ride-along” dog.

animal.description: Nelson is an independent, handsome fella seeking his lifetime companion. He loves to explore with lots of sniffing during walks. He walks well on leash, but he has a tendency to pull at times. Nelson was found as a stray, and it took him a while to adjust to the kennel environment at the shelter. He has come a long way and is now much more comfortable with staff and volunteers. Nelson will greatly benefit from a calm, patient home that will give him plenty of time to decompress. Ongoing socialization and structure will likely help Nelson feel more secure. He can still be nervous at times and may become mouthy when he is anxious. An adopter with cattle dog (or similar breed) experience/ knowledge would be ideal. Nelson will likely need some help with housetraining and perfecting his indoor manners. Nelson would do best in a cat-free home, as well as with children age 14 years or older. We don't know how Nelson feels about other dogs, so they will require a supervised visit with staff prior to adoption. Please consider giving Nelson the love and understanding that he deserves and apply to meet him!

animal.description:
Ace is an approximately 2-year-old neutered male 8lb. Toy Poodle and has quite the story to tell. Ace is a tripod meaning he only has three legs; the right front leg was amputated back in 2019 after it broke when he fell off the kitchen counter. In 2020, the left front leg broke when his then owner was throwing heavy boxes in the backseat and evidently didn't realize he had moved from the front seat to the back.

He came to Speaking of Dogs Rescue in May 2020 from an urgent care clinic when his owner could no longer care for him. We took him directly to an orthopedic surgeon where he underwent surgery to save the only front leg he had left. His foster mom is a vet tech and did everything right but unfortunately after 10 weeks of healing time, the x-rays showed the break had not healed. We became aware of a new technique involving a 3-D printer that might work for Ace. After the consult and workup, we were over the moon to hear that Ace was a candidate for the procedure. Another 10 weeks went by and when the call came from the orthopedic surgeon we were ecstatic: the surgery was a success!

He is now ready for his new life and family, so here's what we know:

He greets everyone with enthusiasm and pleasure. So far, he hasn't met a person he hasn't liked.
Ace is, without a doubt, the sweetest, kindest and bravest dog we know. He never complains, he's always ready with wags and kisses for his caregivers and is king of cuddles.
A primary focus of his care, besides all the cuddles and kisses he's going to be expecting, is to keep him safe and manage his mobility for the rest of his life.
He is still learning what he can safely do and not do and needs his new family to help keep him managed.
He is easy going, likes curling up and relaxing.
Enjoys little walks, sniffing about and exploring.
Needs a safe environment where he can be all the dog he can be, but also avoid any further injuries.
A one-level home would be ideal.
Safety and mobility can be challenging for a three-legged dog.
Ideally his forever home will provide:

Traction for him - a carpeted home or one that has lot of runner rugs for traction to help him move safely. Another possibility would be grip boots or socks and keeping the fur of his feet short.
A healthy and fit body - Ace should stay slim, so he does not have any extra weight to carry around.
Ace should either be fed a good joint/mobility diet or a joint supplement forever.
Ace will benefit from a safe exercise routine and /or possibly even a preventative rehabilitation program.
Ace is crate trained and sleeps overnight in it. This keeps him safe when everyone is sleeping and unable to watch him.
Ace prefers not to be in the crate otherwise and will get anxious in a crate through the day and is currently anxious when on his own. He's had 24-hour care throughout his post-op recovery and is used to having someone always with him.
Ace's surgeon has recommended assistance on and off of the couch or bed as well as supervision to prevent him from jumping off and reinjuring himself.
A follow up x-ray of his leg in May which will give us more of an idea about his future limitations and freedoms.
Ace is housetrained but has almost always been only on a leash or in his "spot" a mat or bed, which he happily stays in (mostly).
Ace will need regular grooming including keeping his nails short to help him move around the best he can.
Although he is great with other dogs, he should be the only dog so he doesn't injure his leg playing or jumping with another dog.
If he breaks his leg again, he will lose it, so he needs an adopter who will be super vigilant and devoted to his care and good management.
He is a young dog with lots of good times ahead of him; he needs a committed adopter so he can live a safe, happy and full life.

animal.description: Panthea at your service. What could I do for you? I ask this question because I am here for you! I am a caring girl that is always interested in your well-being. People say that owners are there for their dogs and this is true to some extent, however, I will be there for you when you need me most. For example, in the morning I will wake you up like an alarm clock. This may be because I have to go outside or I am hungry, however, I am really getting you out of bed so you can start your day. Throughout the day I will remind you that I need to go outside and use the restroom. Sure, I have to go; however, this is making you get more exercise. I see you watching that silly reality show and I will bring you my favorite toy. Sure, I want to play; however, I am really saving your brain from turning to mush by watching that silliness. Sometimes I will track a little bit of mud into the house. I do this so you clean the floor that already needed to be cleaned prior to my mess. I am helping you keep the house clean. As you can see, I am a fantastic asset to have around and will always help you. Just give me some food, water, love, care, and attention and our relationship will be stronger than any you could ever imagine. I am excited to go home with you ASAP where I will really get to work for you.

animal.description:
APPLICATION INSTRUCTIONS ARE INCLUDED BELOW - PLEASE READ TO THE BOTTOM!  If this post is up, the dog is still available.   We will take it down when the dog is no longer available.

Zara is a happy, energetic dog who will provide her family with plenty of love and cuddles. At a little over 1 year old she still has a good bit of puppy in her, she loves to run and play ball. Zara was found as a stray and has been in a foster home with SSCR since November 29th. She currently weighs 45 lbs and will not get any bigger.  Zara is housebroken and crate trained. And although she is a good car-rider, she needs some encouragement to get into the car.  

Zara plays well with her foster siblings and has no interest in being the alpha dog. She plays well with children but due to her energy level we think she would be better suited for a home with children over the age of 12.  Zara takes a little time to warm up to new people, but once she does she can be very snuggly, and she loves belly rubs.  She has been living in a home with cats and has shown no aggression towards them.

Zara is still learning that a leash is not a bad thing, and her walking skills have improved. She may at one time have been spooked by a door (house) and is sometimes wary of coming in if she feels confined. She is being trained with the 'touch' recall command and is making progress in that area.

Zara will require a home with a fully fenced yard, and the fence needs to be 6 feet high because of how agile she is.  When left to her own devices, Zara will get bored and jump over shorter fences.  She LOVES to wrestle and play, so having a young dog who will play with her will be ideal.  We will require at least one other dog in the home, as Zara is much more comfortable when she has another dog to follow.  She knows sit and is learning not to jump, her new home would benefit to continue her training.  Zara is what we call a "work in progress"  :)

If you are interested in giving Zara the permanent, loving home that she deserves, please submit an application through this link. And please read through to the end of this page! When you submit the application through this form, it will email the pdf version over to us. (Please do not print and mail it as it will take much longer for us to receive it!) https://form.jotform.com/202046006590041

Due to the ever changing COVID19 situation, we will continue to adapt our process. At this time, we are not scheduling public events or meet-and-greets in public. We will move straight to the home visit portion of the process, and we are happy to spend ample time with you there as you get to know the dog you are interested in. We ask that an application is filled out in advance of us setting up a home visit.

Details about the organization, the adoption process, and our adoptable dogs can be found on our website at www.lovethemutt.org. Please note that a home visit is a required part of our adoption process. Due to this, we are only able to consider applicants within a 45 mile radius. In some cases, we may extend this radius at our discretion. The adoption fee is $200. This is non-negotiable. Information about the adoption process can be found on our website under the Adoption Process tab. If you have additional questions, please email us at steppingstonesrescue@gmail.com.

animal.description:
HANK HAS FOUND HIS SMILE?

Part I of II - next post contains video of Hank on his first day at his foster home.

Update on Hank the shepherd we rescued 12-8-20. Poor Hank lived in a feces/muddy/wet outdoor kennel for years. Having been a house dog at one time...

Hank had to go to the vet immediately because of his ears. They were in pitiful shape with bacteria and rods. He has had them cleaned and treated and has been on an antibiotic. He will be fully vetted 12-30-20 and barring no surprise health issues or, complications, we will begin accepting applications for him. 

What you need to know about sweet Hank:

Male, 6 year old, German Shepherd. Plays well with other dogs and is currently in a foster home with two other male Shepherds of equal size and they love playing! Crate trained. Housebroken and a snuggle bug. He will require a fenced in yard. German Shepherd experience is preferred. 

Video of Hank playing with his two adopted, foster brothers (Jaxson and Judd nka Panzer) in the next post.

We adopt within a 4 hours driving distance of Toledo, Ohio. Our adoption fee is $350 and covers neuter, heartworm testing, microchip, DHLPP, Bordatella, rabies and fecal float. Please read our FAQ section and adoption application in their entireties before inquiring or, applying. We do not pick adopters based on first come, first served. We try to match our rescues with the best homes for them.

https://www.deaconshope.org/faq.html

https://www.deaconshope.org/adoption-application.html

animal.description:
Meet Brutus! Don't be fooled by his name this boy is anything but rough and tumble.  Brutus is a sweet and loveable 7 year old Boxer/Pit mix who loves all people, kids and dogs!  He is confident without being pushy and easy going without being a push over. 
Brutus would make a nice addition to any home.  He has the best of both worlds as far as qualities go because Brutus is able to take a long hike or go on a brisk run and then come home and snuggle on the couch.  What more could any dog owner want?  Brutus is up to date on all of his vaccinations and is neutered as well. He has also been working on walking well on a lead and crate training.  All he needs now is a loving forever home.

**PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING**

If you are interested in adopting any of the puppies, our adoption fee is $495 ( puppies) $375 (adults) which includes transportation from the South and we do suggest putting a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several littermates.

**Please understand that we are a volunteer based organization. While our volunteers try to answer all emails/questions as quickly as possible, below please find answers to some of our most frequently asked questions. We ask that you please read these FAQ's to see if your question has already been answered before emailing additional questions:

- If a dog or puppy is listed on Petfinder, they are still available. Please do not email asking if they are still available. If a dog or puppy is still listed, then we are still accepting applications :-) We do not go on a first come first serve basis, but on best fit for the family and most importantly, the puppy or dog.

- We are taking our best guess on breed and size when fully-grown (or already an adult), based on the puppy's/dog’s physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. We rarely are able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. 

- Our dogs/puppies are either at our Adoption Center in Brewster, NY, in foster care, or are adopted straight from transport. An application is necessary to meet any dog/puppy. Often, dogs and puppies are spoken for before they arrive. Many people feel more comfortable with a meet and greet which we completely understand and respect, however please know you are taking a chance of that puppy/dog getting adopted by someone else before hand.

- The way to start the process for any dog or puppy is by filling out an application. Applications for foster or adoption can be found at www.snarrnortheast.org and by clicking either adopt or foster from the main menu. If you fill out an application, please make sure you answer all the questions in as much detail as possible and that you receive a confirmation email, otherwise we did NOT receive it.

animal.description: Meet Smoke! This handsome guy was surrendered to the shelter because he did not get along with the other dog in the home. Smoke is about 3 years old, fully vetted, and ready to find the right home. Smoke has done well meeting some of the dogs at the shelter, so a meet and greet would be a must prior to adoption if you already have a dog! Smoke is potty trained and he has some basic obedience training and he knows some basic commands. Smoke has a little separation anxiety when he is left alone but it is much worse when he is in a crate. Smoke does fine if he is left out while he is alone, but he will break out of a kennel if you try to leave him in one. Smoke is afraid of fireworks but doesn't seem to have any problems with other loud noises like thunderstorms or vacuums. Smoke prefers to be a homebody and gets anxious in the car. He was described as friendly, playful, outgoing, energetic, and nervous around new people. They told us that Smoke needs some time to open up to new people but that once he does he is very loving! If you would like to meet Smoke give us a call to schedule an appointment!

animal.description:
Whiskey will make you feel good. A Husky mix aged to perfection at one year, Whiskey is mellow and a genuine pleasure. He’s neat: housebroken and rarely chewing on things he shouldn’t. He only barks appropriately.

Sweet and warm, Whiskey loves his people, following them from room to room. While leery of new people, once trust is established, he is snuggly and appreciative of any attention. He lived with a family with young children in the past, before being surrendered due to a move. Whiskey loves to play — whether it’s fetch with his spiked ball, chewing on his rubber or stuffed toys, or just romping with other dogs. 

This guy’s the real deal. Consider Whiskey. Straight up.

Interested in adopting this dog? Visit our website (http://www.SecondCityCanineRescue.org) to fill out an application and to find out where this dog may be shown this weekend.

We love our dogs. We want happy lives for all of them and are looking for the home that provides the best fit for each dog’s individual needs. Please understand that there may be multiple families interested in this dog. Come to the show to find out if this dog is the right fit for you — it's helpful to bring all family members and current dogs. 

Also, please know that the breed mix listed is simply a guess. In most cases, we don’t know their background. We encourage you to base your decision on individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on our guess.

Please understand, we only adopt our animals out near the Chicagoland area. Questions? Email us at adoptions@sccrescue.org. Hope to see you become part of the SCCR family!

animal.description:
Emotionally sensitive blockhead seeking a shoulder to lay my head upon....could it be you?
 
Here's the thing, I'm awkward at first. I don't like new people, or change... I like my routine. No need for this newfangled nonsense. It's really scary and I have a hard time at first. With patience I have come around to the staff here and now I have a fan club of ladies who argue over who gets to take me out. I'm not complaining!
 
Once I come out of my shell I am a complete goober. I am all about hugs, cuddling and the occasional play bow or short zoomie. I make the staff laugh constantly with my silly personality and I won them over pretty fast. But really I am in it for the cuddles. I am happy to sit and be pet with my head in your lap for hours. I do like my time outside but I am perfectly content inside with my humans too (especially if it's cold... I am not a fan. And don't even get me started on this snow stuff). I am probably going to need to meet folks a few times before I'm ready to leave my friends here, but patience is a wonderful thing! I'm looking for an adult only home, kids would be too scary for a big baby like me. I may be able to live with a dog, but I don't like dogs who come on too strong as I take my time to get to know new friends. I have lived with cats before, and I could potentially do it again with a very slow introduction and a cat who is used to dogs (I'm a big guy!).
 
If I sound like the guy for you, please call the shelter at 603-472-3647 to speak with an adoption counselor.

**Do not apply if you don't meet the criteria listed here**

Hickory is not ready for her forever home until 1/31, but we would love to have furever homes lined up for the Mother Goose pups!

NOTE.... this is a 15 year commitment!!

The puppies are Siberian Huskies. Both Mom and Dad are Huskies. To be eligible to adopt you must have breed experience. Their adoption area is within driving distance to our vet in Davidsonville, MD, where they will be spayed and neutered late May.... NO EXCEPTIONS!! They need homes who have other young, playful dogs and families who will not leave them for long periods of time. No small animals, small children or apartments. Remember, puppies are susceptible to disease, until they are fully vaccinated at 4 months of age. You must have a plan to keep them safe until they're fully vaccinated while properly socializing them. If you are interested and can provide the type of home they need, you can apply on our website.

We will not respond to your application if you do not meet the criteria above. We will be matching puppies to families based on their personality.

www.huskyrescueteam.org
~~Husky Education And Rescue Team is a foster based rescue. Our dogs are in our foster homes all up and down the east coast. We do not have a facility in which you can visit. We find this a huge benefit because we learn our dogs and are able to educate our adopters on what it's like to have them live in your home. Part of our process, once pre-approved, is to speak with the foster for the dog you're interested in. If you're still interested in adopting from our rescue the first step is to complete our adoption application online at www.huskyrescueteam.org/apply

If you have additional questions please email info@huskyrescueteam.org

animal.description: My name is Nutmeg and I'm looking for my forever home. I spent my first 9 years as a breeding mama in a puppy mill, so living in a house with people is new for me. At first I was scared, but now I really like this new life! My foster family says that I'm a very loving and affectionate girl who is good with people and kids (there are 3 boys here). There is another Shiba here too and at first I was grouchy and territorial, but after a couple of weeks, we've become good friends. So if you have another nice dog at home, it might take me a while to feel comfortable with them. I have not yet met any cats. So far, my foster family has learned that I like treats and chew toys, but I don't like being alone and will howl if I'm left by myself for a long time. But I sleep in my crate just fine as long as I know someone is nearby. They've also learned that I will try to sneak out of open doors, so my forever family will need to take precautions to prevent escapes, especially if I think they're leaving me behind! I really enjoy exploring the fenced in yard at my foster home and going for short walks. After being confined for so many years, I'm still building up the strength in my hind legs and getting the hang of stairs. But my foster humans stand next to me and take it slow so they can help me if I stumble. I weigh about 25 lbs and am spayed and vaccinated and fully potty trained (foster mom and dad are so proud of me for not having any accidents!). If you live in the midwest and are looking for a friendly, loving best friend, then I'm your girl! I am being fostered in the Indianapolis area. Visit www.savingshibas.com/adopt to download an application to become approved as a SIRA adopter.

animal.description:
Breed: Staffordshire Terrier
Sex: Male
DOB: ~05/08/17
Weight: 55 lbs
Energy Level: Medium
Personality Type: Chill, Best Buddy, Adventurous, Fun, Goofy, Introverted
Good with: Adults 
History: Transferred from animal control/Stray
Ideal Home: Family or individual capable of handling a strong dog. No other pets or children. Fence preferred.
Special Info: May know ""sit"". Loves to give kisses. He seems to ride well in the car. Has a great ""sploot""! will benefit from working with a force-free trainer (one session included with adoption).

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

Hickory is not ready for her forever home until 1/31, but we would love to have furever homes lined up for the Mother Goose pups!

NOTE.... this is a 15 year commitment!!

The puppies are Siberian Huskies. Both Mom and Dad are Huskies. To be eligible to adopt you must have breed experience. Their adoption area is within driving distance to our vet in Davidsonville, MD, where they will be spayed and neutered late May.... NO EXCEPTIONS!! They need homes who have other young, playful dogs and families who will not leave them for long periods of time. No small animals, small children or apartments. Remember, puppies are susceptible to disease, until they are fully vaccinated at 4 months of age. You must have a plan to keep them safe until they're fully vaccinated while properly socializing them. If you are interested and can provide the type of home they need, you can apply on our website.

We will not respond to your application if you do not meet the criteria above. We will be matching puppies to families based on their personality.

www.huskyrescueteam.org
~~Husky Education And Rescue Team is a foster based rescue. Our dogs are in our foster homes all up and down the east coast. We do not have a facility in which you can visit. We find this a huge benefit because we learn our dogs and are able to educate our adopters on what it's like to have them live in your home. Part of our process, once pre-approved, is to speak with the foster for the dog you're interested in. If you're still interested in adopting from our rescue the first step is to complete our adoption application online at www.huskyrescueteam.org/apply

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Jagger (aka: Kody, Kody bear, Kodiak) is a Shepherd X with an approximate DOB of 5/14/2020. Jagger weighs in at approx. 50 lbs. He is a fun and playful pup with A LOT of energy who would benefit from an active lifestyle. Jagger loves to go on walks, car rides and hikes. He is a shadow and wants to follow you where ever you go. He also likes to go out frequently and run around the back yard. Jagger knows some basic commands and will do well with continued training and learning as he is a very intelligent dog. He is very treat motivated and loves a midday Kong filled with kibbles and treats.

Jagger likes to play with his toys, chewing on bones and playing fetch. Jagger is an aggressive player who is very mouthy and nippy when playing, and needs work on gentler pay, for this reason it is best if he is not in a home with children under age 12. We are working on calming him down when he get really feisty, but he is still young and wants to play hard. Jagger was in a previous home with another dog who was more possessive of their food and treats and Jagger did not take cues to stop playing or biting on the dog. For this reason, Jagger would do best in a home where he is the only dog, or with dogs who are tolerant or can be monitored/separated. However, his previous owner said that he did well playing with dogs outside and in doggy daycare/playgroups. Jagger is working on leash manners and does pretty well when he sees other dogs though he likes to try to get to them and he tries to charge moving vehicles, so more leash work is needed. Jagger does bark at other dogs and people through the backyard fence, and he barks in he house when he sees people outside, so no shared walls. Jagger also should not be on a house with cats due to his high prey drive - this is also a reason a fenced backyard would be best for Jagger. Jagger is kennel trained but may whine and bark a bit when he first goes in and when he hears people moving about. He sleeps best with a fan or other sound on. Jagger is still a puppy so he will chew on items randomly and should be supervised when out in the house or the yard. Jagger has had a few accidents in the house but does well when let our frequently.

Jagger is a very sweet and loving dog who will cuddle when he is ready to settle down. Jagger is ready for his forever home, if you would like to meet him in person fill out an application.Interested in adopting this lovable animal? Please go to our website www.wagsmn.org and fill out an Adoption Application. Once the application is processed, a Wags representative will contact you, answer any questions you may have, and set up a time/location for a meet and greet! A home visit is required prior to adoption.

Thank you for choosing to adopt!

Breed and temperament determination: Wags & Whiskers Animal Rescue attempts to determine breed and temperament using a combination of looks, information provided to us at intake, and our experience with the animal while in our Rescue. We do not guarantee this determination.

**COURTESY POST - EDEN IS WITH OWNER UNTIL REHOMED 

1/4/2021  This is Eden!  She is a beautiful 6 year old American Staffordshire Terrier.  Eden is needing a home where she an be the only dog.  Her current home has two others that she is being kept separate from and she is feeling rather isolated from the family.  She deserves to be someone's couch potato and companion and to feel included.  Eden enjoys long walks and car rides, doesn't show any food aggression or toy aggression, and takes treats gently and knows to sit for her meals.  She is friendly and affectionate with people, however she does have a high prey drive, so she can't be let loose with other animals including cats.  Eden is current on her vaccines, spayed and house trained. If interested in adopting Eden, please complete an application today at www.secondchanceforpets.com.

**NOT ALL PETS LISTED ON OUR WEBPAGE ARE IN OUR FOSTER HOMES. WE ALSO MAKE COURTESY POSTS (CP) FOR FAMILIES NEEDING TO PLACE THEIR PET. 
(SC) MEANS THEY ARE IN ONE OF OUR GROUPS FOSTER HOMES
(CP) MEANS THEY ARE STILL WITH THEIR CURRENT OWNER

animal.description:
**Please apply to adopt only if your are serious about adopting. Vet references are checked**

Lily is that quiet puppy that is often overlooked in a big crowd. With her scruffy little face and puppy kisses, she will win your heart if you meet her. Lily and her sisters are typical playful puppies who play hard and long and fall quickly to sleep to rest up for the next round. She loves to play and run, but is much more timid and content to just hang out than her sisters. She loves being petted and held once she warms up to you, but it does take time. 

Lily is an 9-10week old German Wire-Haired Pointer Mix and she will likely be medium to large when she's done growing. She is up to date on her shots and will be microchipped. She is working on crate and house training, how to play with toys and her manners. She hasn't had any accidents in her crate at her foster's home so far. 

Lily will need a patient, active family willing to work on her social skills as she is new to living with humans. She learns quickly, but will need time and training, like all young puppies. She will need a fenced yard to run in, and she would love to have another dog to play with and show her the ropes.

Beautiful little Iris wants to be in the middle of the action, no matter what it is - she is first on the scene and ready to participate. Iris and her sisters are typical playful puppies who play hard and long and fall quickly to sleep to rest up for the next round. Iris loves to explore and run, but her first love is to be in your lap and have your full attention. Unlike her sisters, she loves new people and sees them as her next best friend. 

She is an 8-week old German Wire-Haired Pointer Mix and she will likely be medium to large when she's done growing. She is up to date on her shots and will be microchipped. She is working on crate and house training, how to play with toys and her manners. She hasn't had any accidents in her crate at her foster's home so far. 

Iris will need a patient, active family willing to work on her social skills as she is new to living with humans. She learns quickly, but will need time and training, like all young puppies. She is the mischievous one of the bunch, and will play with anyone and anything. She wants your FULL attention. She will need a fenced yard to run in, and she would love to have another dog to play with.

animal.description:
MEET SILVER! 
Silver is a 6 year old lab mix that is very enthusiastic about life. She weighs about 60 lbs. She is energetic and playful and loves other dogs. She LOVES people and will melt with an ear rub or neck scratch. She seems to be potty trained, she settles pretty well in the kennel overnight, and would do just about anything for a toy. Eager to please and friendly, this girl would do well with an outlet for her energy, such as lots of walks and ball play.  She loves to play fetch!

**Silver does not, however, do well with cats, and probably wouldn’t do well with other small animals either, as she has a prey drive. **

Could this enthusiastic soul be a good fit in your home and heart? If you have questions about Silver please send us a message on Facebook, or email us at scroungydogs@outlook.com. If you would like to meet Silver please fill out an application at scroungydogs.com.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Any small animal, she has a strong prey drive.

animal.description: Meet Xena. This beauty was brought to the Winchester SPCA in August. A local resident rescued Xena from an online site. She presented with superficial injuries. Xena's wounds have all healed, she's been vaccinated, spayed, and microchipped. She's been well loved in her time at the Winchester SPCA. Xena is one of the friendliest dogs you will ever meet, she has an amazing personality and loves all humans. She loves belly scratches, snow, eating out of your hand, and playing outside. A BARC behavioral assessment has been completed and Xena performed well in all categories except for dog to dog interactions. She will need to be an only dog. We are looking for a special adopter for Xena who can continue the progress we've made at the SPCA and give her the life she deserves. Applications will be accepted at 111 Featherbed Lane in Winchester, VA Tuesday - Friday 10AM to 5PM and weekends by appointment. Veterinary references, landlord checks, and a home visit will required prior to approval.

animal.description:
**PLEASE NOTE** We will NOT consider a home for Rhonda that doesn't have another dog, a fenced in yard, or small children (under the age of 14)

Rhonda is a ~7month old Lab x Terrier x Beagle mix that weighs about 30 pounds. She came to our facility very scared, nervous, and shut down- and will need a patient experienced home to get her settled in and learning how to be a normal dog! We don't think she has had a lot of training, socialization, or consistency in her life so far, but we know with the right home she will get there in no time! She is looking for a home with another CONFIDENT and outgoing dog and a fenced in yard to help her acclimate. At this time she would NOT be a good match for a home with children under the age of 14 due to how shy she is. Having a playful dog around her totally changes her personality and brings out the puppy in this old soul! Her adoption fee is $295 and that includes she is spayed, microchipped, and up to date on all vaccines, flea/tick treatments, and heartworm preventative. animal.description:
Our beautiful Ms Pippy is still looking for a fabulous forever family to call her own.  Over the last 4months in our care we continue to get to know her and tweak what's the best fit. 
Ms Pippy is approx 4yrs old. She was previously used for breeding and then surrendered to a shelter.  She has been fully vetted including spayed, full bloodwork, vaccinated and using monthly prevention. She came to us completely lame on back left so we did xrays.  After being evaluated by our orthopedic specialists, she had FHO surgery and she's recovering beautifully.  Since surgery, we continue  to do Adequan Injections, laser therapy, PEMF mat therapy, and hydrotherapy. She is now back to full activity (walks, romps, etc) and using the leg.  She will need continued work building muscle mass and strength.  She is sweeter than sweet, social, and active (did I mention active).  She is in your face, up your butt, and busy. She also has a very high prey drive and always on the hunt. She will need continued formal obedience training and daily individual training to bring out her best self.  Because of both her medical and behavioral needs, we've been very torn on whether to place her as an only dog or with a friend. The last two weeks (while we've been grieving the loss of our bulldog Boz) has proven she needs a medium/large friend to keep her company or she gets into trouble (barking, chasing, digging, shredding, etc).  She is potty trained and crate trained. She is good in the house but could easily be tempted to counter surf or trash pick. She loves going in the car but does not settle no matter how the long the ride. She doesn't want to miss any possible action.  She loves all toys but if not watched she will shred any type of stuffie and rip out squeakers.  While Ms Pippy is social with people, children and other dogs, she is very forward and she will need a committed adopter to help her transition from pack life to family life. 
If you feel you might be a fit for our Ms Pippy, please visit www.saintlybernards.org and complete an adoption application. 
Thank you in advance.

Jam is a 9 week old Coonhound/Treeing Walker Coonhound, and is full of herself she is playful and sweet and loves to cuddle with her brother Toast. As with all puppies she will need a family that is going to be patient while she is going through potty training and will need to be on a regular potty schedule. She doesn't like being alone so another dog to play and cuddle with would be nice.

Please do some research on the breed as they are hounds and have hound traits, they can be high energy dogs that when full grown will need lots of stimulation and exercise, they do not make good apartment dogs as hounds are very vocal, a securely fenced in yard is a must as with any hound their nose is to the ground and they will follow what they smell and love to run.

They are said to be good family dogs who will be fine with dog courteous children. They are loyal and loving and want to be with their humans all the time.

Highly recommended is getting her into puppy training as soon as possible.

animal.description:
I am truly a sweet boy who enjoys laying on the sofa with my companions, be they dog or human, once I am comfortable with them. I do not have any aggressive traits, neither towards food guarding or in self defense when I feel threatened. In the right home with the right family, I will thrive and relax to enjoy life. With the right care, from the beginning, I will learn and grow to be more comfortable in my new home.

What I need in a home:
- I am more comfortable with women than with men.
- I need a regular steady routine.
- I will do much better in a home that already has a dog that is comfortable and affectionate towards the people in the home.
- I should never be yelled at, scolded or in an environment that has frequent loud abrupt noises because I am very nervous.
- I love to lay on the sofa and I find my crate to be a refuge when I'm frightened or left alone in the house.
- I am still learning to walk on a leash, so having a fenced in yard is required. 
- I need to be free of the presence of children because I find them very frightening and confusing.
- I enjoy chewing bones and toys
- Most of all, I will need an owner that is extremely patient and willing to spend much energy every day to help me become more comfortable and work on basic training.

What I am still working on in my foster home:
- I am still learning to be more comfortable with new people.
- I am working on potty training and will go to the bathroom inside if I am left alone for long periods of time. 
- I have some separation anxiety and will be destructive with things that are left out. 

I am currently being fostered in a home with another dog and a man that has been able to discover the issues and the solutions for my new family. My foster father is willing to work with and help my new family to insure the success of my placement into a safe environment where I can function and become a contributing member of my new family. Please email adoptions@angelsofassisi.org or fill out an adoption application if you are interested in learning more about me!

animal.description:
Bella is a senior lovebug who wants to be anyone and everyone's best friend both four legged and human.  She is well trained in her commands, great on a leash, and wonderful in the car.  Bella would do better in a home with other dogs (she is also cat friendly) and an owner who can keep her company throughout her days.

At 10 years young Bella still has great pep in her step and would love to keep her owners active by taking walks as well as naps on the couch wuth them and snuggling.The best of both worlds!  If you are looking for the perfect companion who will capture your heart, then Bella is the gal for you.



**PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING**

If you are interested in adopting any of the puppies, our adoption fee is $495 ( puppies) $375 (adults) which includes transportation from the South and we do suggest putting a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several littermates.

**Please understand that we are a volunteer based organization. While our volunteers try to answer all emails/questions as quickly as possible, below please find answers to some of our most frequently asked questions. We ask that you please read these FAQ's to see if your question has already been answered before emailing additional questions:

- If a dog or puppy is listed on Petfinder, they are still available. Please do not email asking if they are still available. If a dog or puppy is still listed, then we are still accepting applications :-) We do not go on a first come first serve basis, but on best fit for the family and most importantly, the puppy or dog.

- We are taking our best guess on breed and size when fully-grown (or already an adult), based on the puppy's/dog’s physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. We rarely are able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. 

- Our dogs/puppies are either at our Adoption Center in Brewster, NY, in foster care, or are adopted straight from transport. An application is necessary to meet any dog/puppy. Often, dogs and puppies are spoken for before they arrive. Many people feel more comfortable with a meet and greet which we completely understand and respect, however please know you are taking a chance of that puppy/dog getting adopted by someone else before hand.

- The way to start the process for any dog or puppy is by filling out an application. Applications for foster or adoption can be found at www.snarrnortheast.org and by clicking either adopt or foster from the main menu. If you fill out an application, please make sure you answer all the questions in as much detail as possible and that you receive a confirmation email, otherwise we did NOT receive it.

I am a mixed breed dog. This means I don't have a specific recognizable breed. The rescue uses the following guide which are guesses based on my current size and age for how big I will be when full grown: Mixed Breed (small) up to 25 pounds - Mixed Breed (medium) between 25-45 pounds - Mixed Breed (large) more than 50 pounds. We are setting up adoptions with approved adopters on an appointment basis. We are no longer hosting adoption events at PetSmart until further notice. We are not arranging meet and greets; but appointments to finalize adoptions to limit exposure for all. Our adoptions come with a one week trial period in which if things are not working out, we will refund your adoption fee if you decide to return your newly adopted Faithful Friend. Our adoptions must be done in person and we do not arrange transport to adopters. Our adoption fees vary and we are only able to accept payments by card* at this time but include spay/neuter, heartworm test (dogs), FeLV/FIV test (cats), age appropriate vaccines and deworming, flea, tick and heartworm medication and microchip.

animal.description:
~ THIS IS A COURTESY POST PLEASE DO NOT CONTACT MASSPAWS ~
This dog is with Survivor Tails Animal Rescue (STAR) please fill out an application: survivortails.org or email adoptions@survivortails.org with any questions. Be sure to tell them ARK sent you!  

Are you looking for a dog who’s sweet as sugar? Look no further than Toffee, a 6-year old medium sized lab and boxer mix located in the greater Boston area. She is spayed, up-to-date on vaccinations, and available for adoption in Massachusetts, Connecticut, and New Hampshire! Toffee is the perfect balance between a mellow and energetic nature. She’s simply hoping for a family who will take her outside, feed her lots of treats, and let her love on them!

Toffee loves to spend time outside, either running, playing, and hunting squirrels during the day or hanging out with her people in the evening. When it comes to playtime, she loves many different activities, from playing tug of war to chasing balls to chewing stuffed animals. After a long day of play, Toffee enjoys cuddling on the sofa with her people. She is very attached to her humans, and is the queen of giving sad eyes when they leave the house! 

True to her lab nature, the one thing Toffee loves as much as people and playtime is FOOD! Her favorite treats include carrots and broccoli, and she likes to wander around the kitchen or watch from her dog bed while meals are being fixed. Toffee is also a smart girl who will sit politely and shake paws for treats. Her food motivation could come in handy, as she can be mischievous and needs to be trained not to rip up the mail and bark at passing dogs and the vacuum cleaner.

A sweet dog like Toffee deserves a special home. Her home MUST be pet free, as she has previously picked fights with neighborhood dogs! Toffee also needs an adult-only family. Additionally, she would love to have a fenced yard with plenty of space to run and explore!

Toffee has many favorite things, but the most important one is human love. As a medium-energy, affectionate dog, she would be a great fit for many different families. If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please fill out an application at survivortails.org or email adoptions@survivortails.org with any questions. PLEASE tell them ARK sent you! #ARKforToffee #JustSaveThem

animal.description:
This sweet senior girl is ready for her retirement home. Ellie has had a long road to get to this point. She was not cared for properly for many years and came to be in a shelter Heartworm positive, some growths, underweight and unspayed. She has conquered all these, plus had a dental. She is still moderately active but really loves a cozy couch. Ellie has been fostered with many dogs but would have no problem being an only dog. Her best home is where she would be lavished with attention and love, she has missed many years of this. If you think you could love this very lovable senior please let us know by applying.


If you are interested in adopting Ellie Mae please complete our adoption application on our website at www.bloodhoundrescue.ca Our adoption process and fee are also listed on our website under the application link

Ellie Mae is fostered near Pittsburgh Pennsylvania. With the help of volunteers, transportation to her forever home can possibly be arranged. Please enquire.

animal.description:
Hi future family! My name is Hope and I am a 4 year old girl who is loving life inside! I spent the first few years of my life outside, but now I'm loving snuggling in my crate, with my foster humans, and my foster puppy brother.

I have gained so much confidence in my foster home, meeting new humans and new dogs, who I have all gotten along with. I am learning how to play with other dogs without getting too excited! I love my crate. I sleep in there all night, and go in even during the day when I need a break. I also eat my meals there.

I am up to date on all my shots, and while I am Heartworm positive, I have finished my meds and will be having my treatment very soon and will need about 30 days of downtime to recover.  I have also been spayed. I'm getting better on my leash manners each day, and I am also learning how to sit and lay down. Can we do that together as I recover.

animal.description:
This handsome boy is 10 month old Lenny. He has been through several homes, through no fault of his own. His first family got transferred to Korea and the cost of shipping a dog overseas is really expensive ($6,000 at least). Plus it is stressful for the dog to be transfered and they opted to not take Lenny. They gave him to someone who then saw an opportunity to make some money and sold him on Craig's List. 

The person that bought him did not realize how much energy a young Golden Retriever boy has and living in a tiny apartment was not the right home for Lenny. Even though the owner took Lenny to doggy daycare 3 days a week, it was just not enough to wear the boy down. So Lenny's owner did the very best thing and surrendered him to GRRR to find him a wonderful forever home. 

We had an approved applicant who has with another high energy dog and a big yard for the boys to romp in and a 6 foot fence to keep them safe. So as long as the dogs get along then Lenny will be in his forever home. If something changes and it doesn't work out we will look for another wonderful home for Lenny. You'll get that news on our website first at www.gr-rescue.org. Please visit to see other golden retrievers for adoption. 

To adopt a Golden that you see here, please go to the Golden Retriever Rescue Resource website at www.gr-rescue.org  Read our adoption policies. If you qualify for this dogs adoption and the adoption policies, please write us for an adoption application at grrradoption@yahoo.com  Please provide your city and zip code. Please note, we only adopt to select areas within Ohio, Michigan and Indiana where we can do a home visit by a trusted volunteer. 

Please read our adoption policies on our website prior to inquiring for an adoption application. Thank you!

animal.description:
Tripod alert! Hi, I am Freya! I am an adorable three-legged Pitty. I think I am about four years old, but I am not really sure. I love to be around humans of all ages, though I don’t do well with the humans raising their voices at me. This makes me scared, so I tend to run to my kennel which is my safe place. I also try really hard to always go potty outside, but sometimes if you scare me or get me too excited I pee a little. I feel really bad about it so please don’t yell at me. I just can’t help it. Now that we got that out of the way, let’s talk about all my great qualities. I really love playing with my chew toys, I enjoy playing and snuggling kids, and most of all I just want to lounge with my humans. Sometimes I like to act tough to people passing in the window, but really I am just a big loving baby. I am interested in playing with my foster dog brother and sister, but I can’t meet them just yet. I believe I can be friendly to other dogs though, since I don’t like to be aggressive. I am kind of a chicken at times. I really just want a family of any size to love me, be patient with me, and let them show just how much love I have to give. I have been through a lot in my doggy life, so who is ready to show me the bright side of life with my fur ever family?


Our adoption fee is $260 for dogs over 5 months of age and includes all vaccinations, spay/neuter, micro chip implantation and registration/transfer, heartworm test and much more. Puppies up to 5 months of age are $275 and this includes all sets of puppy vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip implantation and registration and more. To adopt, go to www.fosterpetoutreach.org to complete an application.
Please note: Foster Pet Outreach tries to limit our adoptions to an area within approximately 60 miles of Peoria, Illinois.

animal.description:
Est DOB: 2013
Current weight: 80 lbs but is working to lose another 10 pounds :)
Donut Donnie is a very gentle soul. He is about 8 years old and has had a hard life. He back legs are weak which makes it hard for him to move quickly but he is getting stronger on each walk. When we got him he could barely walk one block now he is trotting and can go a couple of miles at a normal pace.
He gets along with dogs, cats, and kids in his foster home. He is potty trained and will use a bell if needed. He cannot do stairs but can do steps. He has learned to love his orthopedic beds! He is not a barker and comes when called. He has beautiful markings and doesn't shed much. He is on a diet and has lost several pounds but needs to lose more to improve his movement. He is starting to appreciate affection and wants in on it anytime he sees an opportunity. He is low energy but needs regular walks. He just needs a patient, loving family to be his forever family. He will be very loyal in return.
Donut is in a foster home with other dogs, cats, and school aged children that he does well with.
Please consider making this handsome boy a member of your family. As we are a foster based rescue, we do require a completed application to be submitted before we arrange a meet. This can be found on our website at : https://almosthomepetrescue.org/apply-now-1
$150 adoption fee includes core vaccinations, rabies vaccination, heart worm test (in dogs over 6 months of age), microchip and registration, spay/neuter, wormer and flea and heart worm prevention while the dog is in our care. All breed and size categorizations are estimates.

animal.description: Sweet Snowball's story is one of resiliency. This poor mama was found emaciated and chained to wall with her four puppies. Labs and More took this family in and got them the care they desperately needed. Several meals, a warm bed and loving foster home and now Snowball is full of life and ready to go! We think she is around 4 years old is possibly a Terrier and Shepherd mix. She is likely a mix of many breeds with those floppy ears and long, thin legs. Snowball is a playful girl that loves toys and is starting to warm up to the dog she is fostered with. She is learning to share with him and doesn't love every dog she meets so will need a family that will continue her dog socialization. She likes to cuddle close to her people and is always down for a good belly rub. Snowball is still brushing up on her manners, including jumping and getting overly excited at meal time. She's learned "sit" and "come" in her foster home and is working on her crate training. She is a vocal girl that may not do best in a home with shared walls like an apartment. She goes for 2 walks a day with the occasional 3 to 6 mile hike with her foster family. Snowball is still working on her confidence and will need a patient family ready to commit to the continued training and socialization she will need. animal.description:
I am a 10 year old male boxer mix. I was brought the the shelter after being hit by a car. The shelter got me to Ho-Bo Care where I am getting medical treatment. I am in need of a foster home that can help an old man out. 

I have glaucoma in both eyes that was never treated. This has caused me to have no vision in one eye and limited vision in the other. I will have to have eye drops for the rest of my life.

animal.description:
Clyde is a pretty typical hound who leads with his nose and loves food! He is looking for a fenced yard, a home with no small children (under about 10) and a dog buddy or two. He prefers someone to be home more often than not, but is doing well with having other dogs around and may be ok left unattended for 4-6 hours at a time. He is potty trained, knows basic commands and is working on leash skills. While hs is not typically affectionate, Clyde is a great companion to have around. He stays off the furniture, will do anything for a treat, and isn't typically needy once comfortable in your home.

Clyde can be leery with strangers, but warms up just fine with treats and some space. Clyde can get very intent on something (food, trash, prey) and not want to give it up, so training is highly recommended and is why we are recommending he not be homed with small children. He has been very responsive to correction and is starting to cooperate with the humans much more frequently in this area. 

Clyde is up to date on all vaccinations, weighs about 50lbs and comes with a free training session from our partner Just like Magic LLC to start your friendship off on the right foot. 

His adoption fee is $150.

animal.description: Calling all cuddly humans who like to hike and have soft beds! Jules is the sweetest companion, and she never tries to nip at her human companions, and only barks if something alerts her at the front door. She loves walks and running...she'll even enjoy a dip every now and then! She had zero accidents in the house, and rides great in the car. Jules does best with another dog at her side, but would also do well independently. She has zero body odor and the pinkest face, ears, and belly, especially after sun bathing. Jules may have a history of abuse because certain loud noises make her skittish and would do well in a quieter house. Jules is a great eater and drinker. She is currently working on 'sit, 'down, and 'stay, and doing swimmingly. All she asks for is a seat on the bed (if you let her), a couple sloppy kisses, and a few outdoor adventures. Come meet sweet Jules, she would love to be part of a loving and safe home.

animal.description: If your home could use a reliable yard watcher who will be on squirrel patrol, come meet Leia! This curious, independent girl loves to explore. And wow, when it snowed in Austin recently, she was super excited to run in this mysterious white stuff. On warmer days, she's a sunbather who's happy to just hang out in the yard, chewing on bones and rawhide and playing with toys. Leia is a super sweet girl who comes up to her people when she wants their affection, rolling on her back or side for those belly rubs she loves. She lives in foster care with a doggie housemate. They are playful and tolerant of each other, and sometimes give each other kisses. A well-behaved house guest, she has moments of playful spunk, but then is happy to chill and watch Netflix. She's a good listener who understands 'sit' and 'no,' and is happy to sit for treats. And she's a house-trained girl who does well when home alone. She's just so excited to see her person return home! This easy going lady would fit well in most homes, and could either be the only pet or should fit well with a dog sibling of a similar size. She has a possible hip dysplasia, but is still a playful, spunky companion. Come meet her, she'll just ask for a tushy pet and follow you home.

Elkhounds are Norway’s National Dog and are used to track moose (Norsk Elghund meaning “Norwegian Moose Dog”). Wiki says great family dog. 1 Love 4 Animals' volunteers conduct home visits prior to the adoption so applicants must live within 90 miles of Valley Forge, PA. A fence is required for all rescued puppy mill dogs - they tend to be shy and are often a flight risk.

animal.description:
Who doesn’t love them a grumpy boxer? Don’t let that grumpy face fool you though!! Penny is absolutely the sweetest girl in town! She is a 2 year old (35 lbs) girl who was found a stray in rural Louisiana and was brought to a shelter there. Take Paws then brought her into a foster home where she is now a step closer to her forever home!! 

Penny loves people & does well with other dogs. She didn't react to a cat placed in kennel when she passed by one which means she could be good in a home with cats. 

Penny is heartworm negative, spayed, and up to date on vaccines. She’s such a smart and playful girl who knows how to sit on command. She is playful when prompted, and relaxed when it is time to calm down! She’s such an amazing girl who deserves an amazing home, so if that’s you, apply to adopt this sweet baby!

This dog is a Benefactor Dog. His/her increased adoption fee will allow them to act as a benefactor to other dogs in our care that require special medical care and a better chance at adoption.

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (that application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

 The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information.

2021 Adoption Fee Scale:
Benefactor Puppies under 12 months - $500
Benefactor Dogs over 12 months - $400


*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
**ADOPTERS WILL BE REQUIRED TO DRIVE TO CHICAGO, POSSIBLY MORE THAN ONCE-- if you live too far, please do not inquiry as animals will not be shipped**

This little ray of sunshine on this cold Chicago day is Sancho. He's a 2-year-old pomeranian mix who was surrendered to our center recently, when his person simply decided they just didn't want him anymore.

His person rushed him inside, handed him off, and never said goodbye.

It broke his little heart. And, seeing him in such despair has broken all our hearts too.

We'd love for Sancho to get into a warm and loving forever home.

Sancho loves attention, and can be sad when he isn't get any - so we'd like for his forever family to be able to spend the majority of the day with him.

He does have anxiety, and can be vocal at times, so we are doubtful of a life for him with large dogs, cats, or small children, but he does seem to enjoy being around small dogs, so it'd be nice to get him a home where he could have a little dog friend.

He's very smart, very affectionate, and very alert about his surroundings.

animal.description:
Hey ya'll, my name is Sully. I'm a 1 year old Saint Bernard mix. 

I'm a BiG boy! And I'm only going to gain more weight as I fill out. See, my foster mom rescued me from a small shelter. I was covered in ticks. I heard her and my foster human brother mention that I probably had 200 ticks on me that they had to pick off. So as you might expect, I had 2 tick diseases. I have been on medication for the last 3 months to get healthy. I am all healthy now so that's why I say I'm going to be a big huge boy when my body catches up! 

Let me tell you a little about myself. I am a happy boy. I love love love to play and my foster mom has said I need to get ALL my energy out daily so I can relax with the fam. So, I really need an active person or family that will play with me or include me in your active lifestyle. I love to play in water. A lot of time, loud noises scare me and I will look to you to comfort me, as a lot of the time, I want to climb in a lap. My mom says "Sully you are so big." Ha Ha whatever that means. My foster mom says I can be stubborn and sometimes she has to tell me several times to stop doing something. So, I need someone who is patient as I learn what you want me to do. I think training will be a great, fun thing for me to learn so I can focus. I am good with other dogs and love to play. I am a very "in your face dog." So, I definitely need a laid back dog or dogs that won't mind that I am going to annoy them sometimes because I want to play. I would do best with another dog in the home. I sleep in my crate at night and I am potty trained. Sometimes, I will bark when my foster mom leaves home or I hear a leaf blow or something ?, so an apartment life wouldn't be good for me. I don't know if I would be good with cats. I am good with kids, I love everyone, but I don't realize how big I am and come in "way hot" sometimes ha ha. So, I would be best with older kids, probably 10 years and older. My foster mom says I'm the sweetest thing but stubborn. And sometimes I will look at you with the saddest puppy dog eyes when you tell me no! My foster mom says "That doesn't work on me Sully, you have to learn boundaries." Geez! I guess she is right! ? 

I am food protective so I need to be fed separately from other dogs. My foster mom feeds me in my crate and waits until all my foster doggy siblings are done eating.

So, this is all about me. My adoption fee is $150 and includes up to date shots, heart worm test and preventative, microchip and neuter. I can go on a home visit with you for 1 week! If interested in adopting Sully, send an email to adoptions.spspca@gmail.com

animal.description:
Hello Moto!  We would like to introduce you to Moto. He is a 10 year old Maltese/ Poodle Mix who weighs about 16 pounds. Moto arrived in rescue after his previous owner's health failed and he could no longer care for him, and animal services wanted his medical needs addressed right away. His foster mom says: Moto came into foster care after having surgery to remove benign tumor from his back paw and having his tail removed for the same reason. He has fully recovered from his surgeries and even the vet said he is better off without his tail. Now he has a cute little stub!  He suffers from allergies so this will be an ongoing issue for him. We have switched him to grain-free dog kibble and he loves it and it seems to help. He also takes daily antihistamine and needs eye ointment as his eyes have a lot of discharge again due to allergies.  He is a true lump of love. He is living his best life when he is beside you in your chair, just be sure you have room for him as he can be a bit of a chair hog! He will let you know when he needs to go out to do his business, but he will always find the puppy pad if you need to leave him for a bit. He is not a big fan of walking much, so if you are looking for a walking around the neighborhood buddy, he is not your guy, unless you would like to push him in a stroller, LOL. He gets along great with other dogs and loves his stuffed animals. He will be a great companion for anyone looking for a chair buddy!

Moto is neutered, up to date on vaccines, heartworm negative, microchipped and has had his teeth cleaned. 

Moto is fostered in the Orlando area, and his adoption donation is $250. If you are interested in applying to adopt Moto, please visit www.floridalittledogrescue.com to read the adoption process and complete an application! Please note that emails simply asking "Is this dog available" will not be returned, as applications are worked in the order received and availability largely depends on when you apply:) Please also know we do not adopt out of state! Thank you!

animal.description:
Alby is five years old.  An accident rendered him unable to use his back legs and his owners did have surgery in hopes of correcting this condition.  As you can see from the information under special needs, he has regained some use of his legs and may well continue to progress.  We don't know.  His owners said they believe he will get there in walking again because every month he regains more feeling and gets stronger.  

Before Alby's accident he was house trained but now his needs will require being managed.  

Alby is very playful and just wants cuddles and love.  He is great with people and kids like him a lot too!  He grew up with a toddler and there's never been one problem with him and that child.  

Alby is great with other dogs of all sizes and is very playful.  There has never been one incident of him wanting to fight with any dog.  He's a really really sweet dog.  He doesn't foul and he only barks when he hears the doorbell or a new unfamiliar voice.  

He weighs around 25-30lbs right now.  He can scoot around faster than most dogs can run and he's not the least bit intimidated by his handicap. He is an inspiration, and as most special needs dogs, he will melt your heart with his spirit.

Alby knows some commands that he followed very well before surgery.  He still knows them but with his coordination it's harder for him to follow:  go to bed.  stay. sit.  paw (he would give you his paw like nice to meet you).  down.
animal.name: Alby

animal.description:
Meet James Bond! When JB first arrived without a name at his foster home in Texas, his foster mom took one look at his distinguished black coat and white markings and thought that he looked just like he was wearing a sharp Tuxedo!

JB is a 3-year-old Terrier/Chihuahua mix who weighs about 10 pounds. NorthStar found him in a small shelter in South Texas. JB was absolutely terrified and difficult to handle when he came out of the shelter. For a week, he kept to his crate in his foster home, only coming out to do his business, but very closely watching the goings-on in the home. After seeing all the happy doggies romping around in the house, JB slowly warmed up and started to learn how to be a dog again.

JB absolutely LOVES the company of other dogs - he is the smallest dog amongst many larger dogs but loves to run with them and roughhouse and then lay down and cuddle with them and watch TV. He even likes cats! JB is housetrained and also good about being crated.

JB does not like to be picked up - he may have been abused at some point in his life. We do not recommend a home with children, and he will definitely need time to warm up when he arrives in NJ. He must go to a home with a doggy companion and a patient and gentle adopter. We recommend a home with a fully fenced and secure yard since he is too scared to walk on a leash.

If you feel that you have the kind of home that JB needs & would like to make him part of your family, please fill out an application at www.northstarpets.org & be sure to ask for him by name...that's Bond, JAMES BOND TX!
animal.name: James Bond TX
